1
00:00:30,517 --> 00:00:32,060
So

2
00:00:33,353 --> 00:00:36,022
you really don't have an option

3
00:00:36,063 --> 00:00:37,857
about whether or not you're going to

4
00:00:37,898 --> 00:00:40,317
develop a vision for your life.

5
00:00:40,720 --> 00:00:42,960
You can either develop a

6
00:00:44,520 --> 00:00:46,322
good vision or bad vision.

7
00:00:46,520 --> 00:00:48,080
That's your option.

8
00:00:48,288 --> 00:00:52,535
Or you can live out your vision or someone else's.

9
00:00:53,360 --> 00:00:55,413
There's no no-vision option.

10
00:00:56,200 --> 00:00:59,120
If you have poor vision,

11
00:01:00,440 --> 00:01:02,752
immature and hedonistic,

12
00:01:02,803 --> 00:01:05,129
that might be a good way of thinking about it,

13
00:01:05,160 --> 00:01:09,174
then the vision that you impose on the world is

14
00:01:09,360 --> 00:01:11,927
merely a consequence of your short-term whims.

15
00:01:12,760 --> 00:01:15,304
You're going to be governed by something,

16
00:01:16,013 --> 00:01:17,807
and you need to know that.

17
00:01:18,474 --> 00:01:20,392
And there isn't much difference between

18
00:01:20,434 --> 00:01:22,310
being goverened by something and being

19
00:01:22,352 --> 00:01:24,055
possessed by something.

20
00:01:24,080 --> 00:01:26,606
And that's a useful thing to know, too, because

21
00:01:26,640 --> 00:01:28,107
if you have any sense at all,

22
00:01:28,240 --> 00:01:30,775
you'd want to be possessed by the right thing,

23
00:01:30,800 --> 00:01:33,153
because if you're possessed by the wrong thing,

24
00:01:33,194 --> 00:01:34,904
you're going to be in so much trouble,

25
00:01:34,946 --> 00:01:36,155
you can hardly imagine it.

26
00:01:36,197 --> 00:01:38,495
And not only are you going to be in trouble,

27
00:01:38,520 --> 00:01:39,825
you're going to be trouble

28
00:01:39,867 --> 00:01:41,566
to everyone that you encounter.

29
00:01:41,591 --> 00:01:43,920
And that seems like a very bad plan.

30
00:01:44,720 --> 00:01:48,760
And it's not necessary.

31
00:01:50,080 --> 00:01:53,600
So it would be better to do the better thing.

32
00:01:54,337 --> 00:01:58,415
And so I entitled this relatively brief course,

33
00:01:58,440 --> 00:02:01,520
Vision and Plan: Theory and Practice.

34
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:04,012
That's a repetitive title.

35
00:02:04,640 --> 00:02:06,931
A vision is a broad theory,

36
00:02:07,240 --> 00:02:10,440
and a plan is a narrow and focused vision.

37
00:02:11,200 --> 00:02:14,400
And so a broad vision focuses

38
00:02:16,120 --> 00:02:18,160
to a point that can be implemented.

39
00:02:18,520 --> 00:02:21,151
And so what I'm going to do with you over the next

40
00:02:21,200 --> 00:02:22,527
hours is

41
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:25,405
describe to you

42
00:02:25,920 --> 00:02:28,198
how you might conceptualize a vision

43
00:02:28,480 --> 00:02:30,951
in the broadest possible sense,

44
00:02:31,600 --> 00:02:33,400
so that you understand deeply

45
00:02:33,840 --> 00:02:36,400
why doing so is necessary, so

46
00:02:36,872 --> 00:02:39,215
that you understand the consequences of doing it

47
00:02:39,249 --> 00:02:40,500
properly and you understand

48
00:02:40,542 --> 00:02:42,502
the consequences of doing it improperly.

49
00:02:42,544 --> 00:02:44,935
Then we're going to take that general conceptual

50
00:02:44,962 --> 00:02:47,173
scheme, and we're going to focus it down to the

51
00:02:47,214 --> 00:02:49,675
point where it becomes practically implementable.

52
00:02:49,716 --> 00:02:51,885
Because one of the things

53
00:02:51,960 --> 00:02:55,040
you might most want to do if you become

54
00:02:55,240 --> 00:02:58,215
psychologically or philosophically informed is

55
00:02:58,240 --> 00:03:01,400
to understand how you take that broader

56
00:03:01,680 --> 00:03:04,132
conceptualization and make it relevant

57
00:03:04,216 --> 00:03:06,415
and implementable within

58
00:03:06,440 --> 00:03:07,940
the confines of your own life.

59
00:03:07,982 --> 00:03:10,108
Then you have the advantages of the broader

60
00:03:10,160 --> 00:03:11,943
philosophical view, but also something

61
00:03:11,985 --> 00:03:13,815
to do that's extraordinarily practical.

62
00:03:13,840 --> 00:03:17,198
And I would say that abstract ideas become

63
00:03:17,239 --> 00:03:18,991
meaningful when they're implementable.

64
00:03:19,033 --> 00:03:20,617
That's a good thing to know if you're

65
00:03:20,659 --> 00:03:21,794
ever talking to people

66
00:03:21,868 --> 00:03:23,335
and you want to motivate them,

67
00:03:23,360 --> 00:03:25,038
if you have a broad-scale vision.

68
00:03:25,079 --> 00:03:26,935
Maybe you're trying to organize people

69
00:03:26,960 --> 00:03:28,560
to engage in some endeavor.

70
00:03:28,720 --> 00:03:31,055
That could be your family or your business

71
00:03:31,080 --> 00:03:33,520
compatriots, your friends, any sort of occasion.

72
00:03:33,711 --> 00:03:35,775
You want to give them the general picture,

73
00:03:35,800 --> 00:03:37,840
but then you also want to be able to specify

74
00:03:37,882 --> 00:03:40,255
for them exactly what they need to do.

75
00:03:40,280 --> 00:03:42,575
And what they need to do is how they need

76
00:03:42,600 --> 00:03:44,929
to transform the way they look at the situation

77
00:03:44,971 --> 00:03:47,400
and how they need to reconstruct their actions.

78
00:03:47,681 --> 00:03:49,850
And so we're going to go from the general to

79
00:03:49,892 --> 00:03:53,353
the specific over the course of this discussion.

80
00:03:53,720 --> 00:03:56,255
So we'll start very general.

81
00:03:56,280 --> 00:03:58,415
I want to present you with a way

82
00:03:58,440 --> 00:04:01,255
of conceptualizing the world of experience

83
00:04:01,280 --> 00:04:02,840
in the broadest possible sense,

84
00:04:03,240 --> 00:04:04,696
because that'll give you

85
00:04:04,880 --> 00:04:08,120
the initial introduction into why

86
00:04:09,440 --> 00:04:12,480
developing a vision is inevitable and necessary.

87
00:04:13,785 --> 00:04:17,706
So this is a Daoist image of the world,

88
00:04:18,520 --> 00:04:21,440
and it isn't the image that people in the West are

89
00:04:22,280 --> 00:04:24,800
generally familiar with,

90
00:04:25,240 --> 00:04:28,173
because we tend to think of the world as material,

91
00:04:28,200 --> 00:04:31,280
but the world is not merely material,

92
00:04:32,400 --> 00:04:36,055
not least because the world is at least material

93
00:04:36,440 --> 00:04:39,433
and information, and information is not,

94
00:04:41,080 --> 00:04:43,394
it's not material in a reductive sense.

95
00:04:43,800 --> 00:04:46,575
The classic view of the world,

96
00:04:46,600 --> 00:04:49,495
even in the West, was more like the Daoist view.

97
00:04:49,520 --> 00:04:51,080
And the Daoist view is that

98
00:04:51,693 --> 00:04:54,015
the world of your experience, and maybe even

99
00:04:54,040 --> 00:04:56,815
the world as such, is made up of two components.

100
00:04:56,840 --> 00:04:58,788
One, you could conceptualize as chaos,

101
00:04:58,872 --> 00:05:01,320
and the other, you could conceptualize as order.

102
00:05:01,800 --> 00:05:04,204
And in the yin and yang symbol,

103
00:05:04,245 --> 00:05:07,206
which is two serpents, by the way, head to tail,

104
00:05:07,248 --> 00:05:09,374
the black serpent is chaos,

105
00:05:09,416 --> 00:05:11,840
and the white serpent is order.

106
00:05:11,960 --> 00:05:14,587
And the black serpent is generally identified

107
00:05:14,629 --> 00:05:16,214
with the feminine, which is not

108
00:05:16,255 --> 00:05:18,200
the same as the female or the woman.

109
00:05:18,225 --> 00:05:20,717
And the white serpent is

110
00:05:20,759 --> 00:05:23,011
characterized as masculine.

111
00:05:24,480 --> 00:05:26,764
I'll describe why that is as we progress.

112
00:05:26,806 --> 00:05:28,182
So what does this mean,

113
00:05:28,224 --> 00:05:31,600
that the world is chaos and order, in its,

114
00:05:32,960 --> 00:05:34,382
what would you say,

115
00:05:34,407 --> 00:05:36,564
initial differentiated conception?

116
00:05:36,606 --> 00:05:38,816
You could think of the world of experience as

117
00:05:38,857 --> 00:05:40,692
a transcendent unity, and that would be

118
00:05:40,735 --> 00:05:41,818
the unity of all things.

119
00:05:41,860 --> 00:05:43,684
And then you could think of that unity as

120
00:05:43,709 --> 00:05:44,760
falling into pieces.

121
00:05:44,960 --> 00:05:48,760
Each of us is a piece of an overarching unity.

122
00:05:49,080 --> 00:05:52,720
You might ask, well, what is the most

123
00:05:52,960 --> 00:05:56,600
fundamental initial breakdown of the unity?

124
00:05:56,880 --> 00:05:58,240
And the answer to that is,

125
00:05:58,265 --> 00:05:59,655
well, it's chaos and order.

126
00:05:59,680 --> 00:06:02,215
And it's always that, no matter where you are.

127
00:06:02,240 --> 00:06:04,295
And so here's a way of understanding that.

128
00:06:04,337 --> 00:06:06,589
No matter where you are, there are things that are

129
00:06:06,631 --> 00:06:08,000
happening that you understand,

130
00:06:08,048 --> 00:06:09,758
and there are things that are happening

131
00:06:09,800 --> 00:06:11,218
that you don't understand.

132
00:06:11,259 --> 00:06:13,655
And the things that you understand, that's order.

133
00:06:13,680 --> 00:06:15,054
That's the domain of order.

134
00:06:15,080 --> 00:06:16,931
And the things that you don't understand,

135
00:06:16,972 --> 00:06:18,515
that transcend your understanding,

136
00:06:18,557 --> 00:06:20,225
that's the domain of chaos.

137
00:06:20,320 --> 00:06:22,655
And chaos is also the domain of potential,

138
00:06:22,680 --> 00:06:25,615
because in the things you don't understand is

139
00:06:25,640 --> 00:06:27,898
the possibility of new knowledge,

140
00:06:28,600 --> 00:06:30,935
new ways of conceptualizing the world,

141
00:06:30,960 --> 00:06:34,654
and new discoveries about your own nature.

142
00:06:35,154 --> 00:06:37,735
And so you can be terrified of the things that you

143
00:06:37,760 --> 00:06:39,415
don't understand and you don't know,

144
00:06:39,440 --> 00:06:41,055
and you can see why that might be,

145
00:06:41,080 --> 00:06:42,661
because they can undermine you.

146
00:06:42,702 --> 00:06:44,370
But by the same token,

147
00:06:44,495 --> 00:06:46,695
in the domain of things you don't understand

148
00:06:46,720 --> 00:06:49,041
is all the potential of the world.

149
00:06:49,520 --> 00:06:51,835
So one of the things that you might think about

150
00:06:51,860 --> 00:06:54,112
deeply is, what would be a good

151
00:06:54,696 --> 00:06:56,760
rule-of-thumb attitude to have

152
00:06:56,880 --> 00:06:59,200
towards the things you don't know?

153
00:06:59,508 --> 00:07:01,495
And one answer to that is to be terrified

154
00:07:01,520 --> 00:07:05,135
into paralysis because of the necessity for change

155
00:07:05,160 --> 00:07:07,880
that an encounter with the unknown might produce.

156
00:07:08,015 --> 00:07:10,255
And the other is to welcome it with open arms

157
00:07:10,280 --> 00:07:14,095
because the you that might emerge as a consequence

158
00:07:14,120 --> 00:07:16,615
of confrontation with what you don't know might

159
00:07:16,640 --> 00:07:19,640
be much better than the you you're stuck with now.

160
00:07:20,120 --> 00:07:22,040
And that's very much worth considering.

161
00:07:23,320 --> 00:07:25,644
How you conceptualize

162
00:07:25,920 --> 00:07:28,375
the stance you take in relationship to the domains

163
00:07:28,400 --> 00:07:31,055
of chaos and order, that's about the most

164
00:07:31,080 --> 00:07:32,994
important decision you ever make.

165
00:07:33,026 --> 00:07:35,615
If you're a tyrant, for example, you're going

166
00:07:35,640 --> 00:07:38,957
to be allied 100% with what you already know.

167
00:07:39,500 --> 00:07:40,209
Right?

168
00:07:40,250 --> 00:07:41,918
Now, the price you pay for that is

169
00:07:41,960 --> 00:07:43,545
that you forego transformation.

170
00:07:43,586 --> 00:07:45,160
Another price you pay for that is,

171
00:07:45,185 --> 00:07:47,815
if you're tyrannical in your alliance with what

172
00:07:47,840 --> 00:07:49,815
you already understand, you're going

173
00:07:49,840 --> 00:07:51,843
to attempt to force that on other people.

174
00:07:51,885 --> 00:07:54,295
And part of the reason you do that is because you

175
00:07:54,320 --> 00:07:56,305
don't have enough faith in your own ability

176
00:07:56,347 --> 00:07:59,058
to confront what you don't understand and change.

177
00:07:59,360 --> 00:08:03,240
It's not wise unless, well, I suppose you could

178
00:08:03,760 --> 00:08:06,375
envision a situation where you

179
00:08:06,400 --> 00:08:08,190
should only abide by what you know.

180
00:08:08,232 --> 00:08:10,400
And I would say, if your life is absolutely

181
00:08:10,442 --> 00:08:12,360
perfect in all of its manifestations

182
00:08:12,402 --> 00:08:14,192
and you couldn't dream of having

183
00:08:14,400 --> 00:08:15,860
anything better, then you can

184
00:08:15,944 --> 00:08:17,698
stick with what you've got.

185
00:08:18,200 --> 00:08:19,215
But if it isn't,

186
00:08:19,240 --> 00:08:21,034
then there's always the possibility

187
00:08:21,076 --> 00:08:22,702
that a little more transformation

188
00:08:22,744 --> 00:08:24,704
on your part might be a good thing.

189
00:08:24,960 --> 00:08:25,255
Right.

190
00:08:25,280 --> 00:08:28,815
Now, there's a deep level of conceptualization

191
00:08:28,840 --> 00:08:30,940
that goes along with that, too, which is,

192
00:08:31,520 --> 00:08:33,920
how should you construe

193
00:08:34,520 --> 00:08:36,960
the domain of possibility or potential?

194
00:08:37,920 --> 00:08:40,600
And I suppose you might say that this is

195
00:08:41,344 --> 00:08:43,895
a question of faith, right?

196
00:08:43,920 --> 00:08:47,000
Because the future is unknown and indeterminate,

197
00:08:47,320 --> 00:08:49,183
it's very difficult to make any

198
00:08:49,811 --> 00:08:53,200
final decisions about its nature.

199
00:08:53,800 --> 00:08:56,985
But you can make a meta-decision, you might say,

200
00:08:57,569 --> 00:09:00,455
that the domain of potential,

201
00:09:00,480 --> 00:09:02,440
if confronted properly, is positive,

202
00:09:02,861 --> 00:09:04,987
and that you could establish a relationship

203
00:09:05,029 --> 00:09:08,520
with it that would bring benefit to you.

204
00:09:09,575 --> 00:09:11,800
That's really the attitude that children have

205
00:09:11,825 --> 00:09:14,920
towards the world, is that they're open to

206
00:09:14,954 --> 00:09:17,373
exploration and discovery within certain bounds.

207
00:09:17,560 --> 00:09:20,735
That's often shattered, that naivety.

208
00:09:20,760 --> 00:09:22,560
That naive openness of children

209
00:09:22,640 --> 00:09:24,600
is often shattered by trauma.

210
00:09:25,080 --> 00:09:27,200
And that tends to turn us into cynics.

211
00:09:27,760 --> 00:09:30,092
But that doesn't mean that the attitude was

212
00:09:30,120 --> 00:09:32,052
fundamentally inappropriate.

213
00:09:32,480 --> 00:09:33,840
There's a Gospel statement

214
00:09:34,262 --> 00:09:36,375
that makes the claim that you can't enter

215
00:09:36,400 --> 00:09:38,265
the Kingdom of Heaven unless you become

216
00:09:38,307 --> 00:09:39,700
like little children,

217
00:09:39,920 --> 00:09:41,852
which is not the same as staying

218
00:09:42,080 --> 00:09:43,853
like a little child, by the way,

219
00:09:43,880 --> 00:09:46,800
and the idea there is that you should strive

220
00:09:46,920 --> 00:09:51,815
to regain the attitude of open acceptance

221
00:09:51,840 --> 00:09:55,029
of what's confronting you as an adult,

222
00:09:55,280 --> 00:09:57,073
even if you've been hurt.

223
00:09:57,323 --> 00:09:59,116
Because if you've been hurt, well,

224
00:09:59,158 --> 00:10:01,735
then you could imagine that you're more afraid

225
00:10:01,760 --> 00:10:03,953
of what you don't know because you've discovered

226
00:10:03,995 --> 00:10:06,372
that it can undermine and destroy you, devour you.

227
00:10:06,414 --> 00:10:08,999
And it's very easy to become cynical and bitter

228
00:10:09,041 --> 00:10:13,575
and rigid as a consequence of that.

229
00:10:13,600 --> 00:10:15,129
But as I said before,

230
00:10:15,160 --> 00:10:17,298
the price you pay for that is that you forego

231
00:10:17,339 --> 00:10:18,590
any further transformation,

232
00:10:18,632 --> 00:10:20,775
and you tend to become a tyrant.

233
00:10:20,800 --> 00:10:22,840
Well, unless you want to become a tyrant,

234
00:10:23,238 --> 00:10:24,960
tyrants tend to live in hell.

235
00:10:25,280 --> 00:10:27,135
So I wouldn't recommend it

236
00:10:27,160 --> 00:10:28,891
unless that's what you want.

237
00:10:29,308 --> 00:10:31,295
And you can be a tyrant to yourself just

238
00:10:31,320 --> 00:10:32,977
like you're a tyrant to other people.

239
00:10:33,019 --> 00:10:34,896
And in fact, that's usually a precondition

240
00:10:34,937 --> 00:10:36,731
for being a tyrant to other people,

241
00:10:36,772 --> 00:10:38,880
which is also a good reason not to be a tyrant

242
00:10:38,905 --> 00:10:40,935
to other people, because you will

243
00:10:40,960 --> 00:10:42,695
bring that attitude towards yourself.

244
00:10:42,720 --> 00:10:44,855
OK, so what have we established?

245
00:10:44,880 --> 00:10:45,446
Well,

246
00:10:46,240 --> 00:10:47,990
we've established that you can

247
00:10:48,160 --> 00:10:50,723
think about your world of experience as

248
00:10:50,748 --> 00:10:53,203
bifurcated into two fundamental realms.

249
00:10:53,240 --> 00:10:55,680
There's the realm of things you don't understand.

250
00:10:55,913 --> 00:10:58,207
You think about that as unexplored territory.

251
00:10:58,249 --> 00:11:00,615
If you want to make it more biological,

252
00:11:00,640 --> 00:11:03,440
animals have to deal with a territory that they

253
00:11:03,560 --> 00:11:05,671
have mastered and understand—

254
00:11:05,713 --> 00:11:07,256
that's their home territory—

255
00:11:07,298 --> 00:11:09,174
and they have to deal with territories

256
00:11:09,216 --> 00:11:11,335
where the predators lurk, let's say.

257
00:11:11,360 --> 00:11:14,535
And animals tend to stick to their home territory

258
00:11:14,560 --> 00:11:15,805
because that's explored,

259
00:11:15,847 --> 00:11:17,681
and they tend to be afraid of their

260
00:11:17,723 --> 00:11:19,475
unexplored territory because

261
00:11:19,516 --> 00:11:21,184
that's where they can be destroyed.

262
00:11:21,212 --> 00:11:23,295
And so this notion,

263
00:11:23,320 --> 00:11:25,920
this metaphysical notion that experience is

264
00:11:25,945 --> 00:11:27,731
characterized by chaos and order,

265
00:11:28,200 --> 00:11:30,400
is also a notion that

266
00:11:30,442 --> 00:11:33,800
can align with a materialistic view of the world

267
00:11:34,360 --> 00:11:37,281
and the psyche as a biological phenomenon.

268
00:11:37,323 --> 00:11:39,408
Your nervous system is set up, really,

269
00:11:39,439 --> 00:11:43,215
to respond with security when you're

270
00:11:43,240 --> 00:11:46,055
in the territory that you understand

271
00:11:46,080 --> 00:11:48,080
and to respond with, first,

272
00:11:48,240 --> 00:11:51,460
fear and then curiosity when you encounter

273
00:11:51,501 --> 00:11:53,336
the territory you don't understand.

274
00:11:53,786 --> 00:11:56,172
Now, for animals, that territory tends to be

275
00:11:56,214 --> 00:11:59,215
more specifically geographical, because, like,

276
00:11:59,240 --> 00:12:01,160
a wolf pack will have its territory or any

277
00:12:01,185 --> 00:12:03,440
given animal will have its physical territory.

278
00:12:03,800 --> 00:12:05,930
Now, we inhabit a physical territory,

279
00:12:05,972 --> 00:12:07,175
which is why, hopefully,

280
00:12:07,200 --> 00:12:09,760
you're comfortable at home and less comfortable

281
00:12:09,785 --> 00:12:11,775
when you make a foray out into the world

282
00:12:11,800 --> 00:12:13,770
to places that you don't know.

283
00:12:14,062 --> 00:12:17,648
But our environment is also conceptual,

284
00:12:18,240 --> 00:12:21,693
and so our conceptual environments are also

285
00:12:21,735 --> 00:12:23,736
divided up into the things we understand

286
00:12:23,778 --> 00:12:25,855
and the things that we don't understand.

287
00:12:25,880 --> 00:12:29,375
And even though we can be at home in our physical

288
00:12:29,400 --> 00:12:30,960
territory and quite secure

289
00:12:31,800 --> 00:12:33,775
in our metaphysical territories,

290
00:12:33,800 --> 00:12:36,400
there are still domains that we don't understand,

291
00:12:36,960 --> 00:12:38,707
edges and frontiers.

292
00:12:39,120 --> 00:12:42,520
And so if you, maybe you have some

293
00:12:46,200 --> 00:12:47,960
primitive understanding of physics,

294
00:12:48,200 --> 00:12:49,633
but you could certainly

295
00:12:49,880 --> 00:12:51,800
appreciate very rapidly that there are

296
00:12:53,280 --> 00:12:54,762
physical theories,

297
00:12:55,040 --> 00:12:57,415
theories developed by sophisticated physicists,

298
00:12:57,440 --> 00:12:59,920
that transcend your understanding.

299
00:13:00,040 --> 00:13:02,560
And you could imagine that there's also a place

300
00:13:02,800 --> 00:13:05,160
between your understanding and those more

301
00:13:05,188 --> 00:13:06,935
sophisticated theories where

302
00:13:06,960 --> 00:13:08,640
you can almost understand.

303
00:13:08,680 --> 00:13:11,975
And you could imagine standing on that edge

304
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:15,095
of almost understanding and being curious

305
00:13:15,120 --> 00:13:19,074
and intrigued and enticed by the possibility

306
00:13:19,116 --> 00:13:20,784
that you might expand your knowledge.

307
00:13:20,826 --> 00:13:21,410
Well,

308
00:13:21,440 --> 00:13:24,080
you're surrounded by a metaphysical territory,

309
00:13:24,840 --> 00:13:27,748
a multidimensional metaphysical territory,

310
00:13:27,790 --> 00:13:30,695
made of all these different domains of knowledge,

311
00:13:30,720 --> 00:13:34,170
and you have some mastery over each of them.

312
00:13:34,212 --> 00:13:36,495
There are elements of them that transcend you,

313
00:13:36,520 --> 00:13:38,674
and there are frontiers and borders that you

314
00:13:38,716 --> 00:13:40,884
could stand on where you would learn.

315
00:13:41,760 --> 00:13:43,261
Here's the thing to know.

316
00:13:43,720 --> 00:13:45,513
You get interested in something when

317
00:13:45,560 --> 00:13:48,307
you're put on the edge of what you know.

318
00:13:49,360 --> 00:13:54,255
That grip of interest is actually a manifestation

319
00:13:54,280 --> 00:13:57,023
of the instinct that drives you to learn.

320
00:13:57,880 --> 00:14:01,480
And you can see now and then that you'll encounter

321
00:14:01,760 --> 00:14:05,680
a book or a talk or a discussion that

322
00:14:07,400 --> 00:14:09,295
maximizes your engagement,

323
00:14:09,320 --> 00:14:12,615
and the maximization of that engagement is

324
00:14:12,640 --> 00:14:15,760
generally a signal that you're in the place where

325
00:14:16,240 --> 00:14:19,541
optimized learning is taking place.

326
00:14:20,200 --> 00:14:22,720
Now, people make the claim,

327
00:14:22,752 --> 00:14:24,545
especially in the modern world,

328
00:14:24,587 --> 00:14:26,714
that life is intrinsically meaningless,

329
00:14:26,760 --> 00:14:29,174
and that's usually a rationalist claim.

330
00:14:29,216 --> 00:14:30,759
I can talk about that later.

331
00:14:30,801 --> 00:14:33,011
But I'm making a phenomenological claim,

332
00:14:33,040 --> 00:14:36,097
which is that there's an instinct of meaning

333
00:14:36,138 --> 00:14:39,040
that signals that you're in a place that's

334
00:14:39,065 --> 00:14:41,120
the border between what you know and what you

335
00:14:41,145 --> 00:14:43,215
don't know, that grips you,

336
00:14:43,240 --> 00:14:46,495
and that that phenomenological meaning is a signal

337
00:14:46,520 --> 00:14:51,280
of transformation and of expansion of adaptation.

338
00:14:51,318 --> 00:14:53,820
And in consequence, it's not something that should

339
00:14:53,862 --> 00:14:57,175
be eradicable by a kind of brainless nihilism.

340
00:14:57,200 --> 00:14:59,908
It's actually the deepest signal you have

341
00:15:00,280 --> 00:15:02,661
that you're in the place that you should be,

342
00:15:02,800 --> 00:15:04,855
if you're transforming into the next

343
00:15:04,880 --> 00:15:06,800
best version of yourself.

344
00:15:07,039 --> 00:15:09,208
So you don't want to forego a relationship

345
00:15:09,249 --> 00:15:10,959
with that, because if you do that,

346
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:12,655
because you're nihilistic, let's say,

347
00:15:12,680 --> 00:15:14,455
and maybe because you've been hurt,

348
00:15:14,480 --> 00:15:16,589
then you're going to destroy your relationship

349
00:15:16,631 --> 00:15:18,632
with the process that could transform you

350
00:15:18,674 --> 00:15:21,301
and allow you to adapt to the world.

351
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:24,012
That seems like a bad idea.

352
00:15:24,664 --> 00:15:27,520
And so it's useful.

353
00:15:27,840 --> 00:15:30,360
People say that they can't live without meaning.

354
00:15:30,960 --> 00:15:34,055
And that's a very strange thing to say if you

355
00:15:34,080 --> 00:15:35,520
think about meaning as something

356
00:15:35,545 --> 00:15:37,495
that's only abstracted or metaphysical.

357
00:15:37,520 --> 00:15:38,678
But if you understand

358
00:15:39,262 --> 00:15:42,120
that meaning is actually a manifestation of the

359
00:15:42,800 --> 00:15:46,530
instinct that signals optimal learning or optimal

360
00:15:46,572 --> 00:15:48,991
transformation, then you can understand why you

361
00:15:49,033 --> 00:15:52,375
might die without meaning, because in some sense,

362
00:15:52,400 --> 00:15:54,200
if you're static, you're not living.

363
00:15:55,444 --> 00:15:58,000
And if you also understand that meaning is

364
00:15:58,080 --> 00:16:00,783
the signal of optimized transformation,

365
00:16:00,840 --> 00:16:02,340
if you really understand that,

366
00:16:02,702 --> 00:16:05,621
then you're immune in some ways to the

367
00:16:06,120 --> 00:16:07,680
corrosive nihilism that says,

368
00:16:07,790 --> 00:16:09,880
"at its core, life has no meaning."

369
00:16:10,080 --> 00:16:10,780
It's like,

370
00:16:12,680 --> 00:16:15,263
I probably figured this out years ago when I was

371
00:16:15,304 --> 00:16:16,700
thinking about music,

372
00:16:17,480 --> 00:16:21,137
because music has the aspect of intrinsic meaning.

373
00:16:21,476 --> 00:16:23,495
If you're listening to a piece of music

374
00:16:23,520 --> 00:16:25,188
that compels you or that you love,

375
00:16:25,229 --> 00:16:27,273
and someone taps you on the shoulder and

376
00:16:27,640 --> 00:16:28,691
tells you that

377
00:16:29,937 --> 00:16:32,855
in the final analysis that nothing you do has any

378
00:16:32,880 --> 00:16:34,800
significance, if you have any sense,

379
00:16:34,880 --> 00:16:37,055
you're going to just push them away and say,

380
00:16:37,080 --> 00:16:39,020
yeah, but I'm listening to the music.

381
00:16:39,160 --> 00:16:43,735
And music is a balance between chaos and order.

382
00:16:43,760 --> 00:16:45,855
It has an element of predictability.

383
00:16:45,880 --> 00:16:48,800
Otherwise, you can't follow the piece of music,

384
00:16:49,166 --> 00:16:51,543
but it has an element of unpredictability because

385
00:16:51,585 --> 00:16:53,116
if it just repeats over and over,

386
00:16:53,141 --> 00:16:54,712
you get bored with it very quickly.

387
00:16:54,754 --> 00:16:56,815
So what a musician does is present you

388
00:16:56,840 --> 00:16:58,455
with a structure of order

389
00:16:58,480 --> 00:17:01,175
and then vary that in an interesting way within

390
00:17:01,200 --> 00:17:02,844
a certain set of parameters

391
00:17:03,095 --> 00:17:05,471
and captures your interest as a consequence.

392
00:17:05,600 --> 00:17:09,480
And the reason that you feel that as meaningful is

393
00:17:09,516 --> 00:17:11,495
because what music is doing is modeling

394
00:17:11,520 --> 00:17:13,561
the way the world actually works.

395
00:17:14,280 --> 00:17:16,880
And so that's also extremely useful to know.

396
00:17:17,026 --> 00:17:20,215
You hear that music is a non-representational art,

397
00:17:20,240 --> 00:17:21,695
but that's actually not true.

398
00:17:21,720 --> 00:17:24,240
It's the most representational art because

399
00:17:24,800 --> 00:17:27,400
it specifies most precisely

400
00:17:28,040 --> 00:17:30,655
that the world is made out of order and chaos,

401
00:17:30,680 --> 00:17:32,455
and that meaning is the appropriate

402
00:17:32,480 --> 00:17:33,953
balance between the two.

403
00:17:33,995 --> 00:17:36,455
And so I would say, if you're conducting your life

404
00:17:36,497 --> 00:17:38,080
properly, so to speak,

405
00:17:38,123 --> 00:17:39,958
it'll have a musical element.

406
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:41,668
It'll have that same kind of meaning

407
00:17:41,710 --> 00:17:43,455
and the things will fall into place

408
00:17:43,480 --> 00:17:45,388
in a relatively musical manner.

409
00:17:45,471 --> 00:17:47,940
You'll see in your life that there are times when

410
00:17:48,200 --> 00:17:50,800
you're in the right place at the right time,

411
00:17:50,884 --> 00:17:52,552
doing the right thing, and things

412
00:17:52,600 --> 00:17:56,095
fall into alignment all around you.

413
00:17:56,120 --> 00:17:58,960
Temporally, they're timed well, and things seem to

414
00:17:59,120 --> 00:18:01,655
exist in a harmonious relationship to one another.

415
00:18:01,680 --> 00:18:04,000
And those are the times of your life that

416
00:18:04,520 --> 00:18:07,535
you would like to have more of,

417
00:18:07,560 --> 00:18:09,650
if you could only figure out how to do it.

418
00:18:09,691 --> 00:18:11,902
And well, partly what we're going to do

419
00:18:11,956 --> 00:18:14,320
in the next hours or so is see if we can step

420
00:18:14,362 --> 00:18:17,073
through understanding how you might manage that.

421
00:18:17,200 --> 00:18:20,492
All right. So you could say, to begin with,

422
00:18:21,320 --> 00:18:22,840
the world is made out of order.

423
00:18:23,880 --> 00:18:26,330
And what does it mean for things to be ordered?

424
00:18:26,554 --> 00:18:28,239
There's a very specific meaning

425
00:18:28,264 --> 00:18:29,940
that's useful to know about that.

426
00:18:29,965 --> 00:18:31,751
You're in the domain of order when your

427
00:18:31,793 --> 00:18:34,128
actions produce the outcomes you intended.

428
00:18:34,671 --> 00:18:36,080
OK, so that's really what it

429
00:18:36,105 --> 00:18:37,620
means to understand something.

430
00:18:37,645 --> 00:18:41,775
If what you're doing produces the results that you

431
00:18:41,800 --> 00:18:44,800
desire, then you're somewhere you understand.

432
00:18:45,096 --> 00:18:46,980
If you're out with your friends,

433
00:18:47,014 --> 00:18:49,455
hypothetically, you're there to have a good time.

434
00:18:49,480 --> 00:18:51,268
If you're in a conversation with them

435
00:18:51,309 --> 00:18:53,269
and the conversation is flowing smoothly,

436
00:18:53,311 --> 00:18:55,980
everyone's happy and laughing, then your

437
00:18:56,760 --> 00:19:00,015
emotions signal to you that the territory defined

438
00:19:00,040 --> 00:19:02,480
by you and your friends and your interaction

439
00:19:02,777 --> 00:19:05,238
is familiar and comfortable and promising.

440
00:19:05,363 --> 00:19:07,281
It's the same thing if you have a meal

441
00:19:07,315 --> 00:19:09,116
with your family and it's going well.

442
00:19:09,158 --> 00:19:12,055
Now, maybe you have a meal with your family

443
00:19:12,080 --> 00:19:14,375
at a vacation and someone throws something

444
00:19:14,400 --> 00:19:15,655
untoward on the table,

445
00:19:15,680 --> 00:19:17,760
which often happens in family gatherings.

446
00:19:18,160 --> 00:19:21,600
Some unresolved issue comes up,

447
00:19:22,480 --> 00:19:24,015
for one reason or another,

448
00:19:24,040 --> 00:19:25,338
like it might habitually.

449
00:19:25,379 --> 00:19:28,135
That's the emergence of unexplored territory into

450
00:19:28,160 --> 00:19:30,884
the domain of what's predictable and positive.

451
00:19:31,720 --> 00:19:33,845
And that produces all sorts of emotional

452
00:19:33,880 --> 00:19:35,680
reactions, often negative,

453
00:19:35,720 --> 00:19:38,280
especially if it happens involuntarily.

454
00:19:39,085 --> 00:19:42,535
So that's another way of starting to understand

455
00:19:42,560 --> 00:19:45,360
what it means to see the world in this way.

456
00:19:46,133 --> 00:19:49,840
So you have what you understand,

457
00:19:51,440 --> 00:19:54,575
which is the domain that you inhabit when your

458
00:19:54,600 --> 00:19:57,364
patterns of attention and action are producing

459
00:19:57,406 --> 00:19:59,055
the desired outcome,

460
00:19:59,080 --> 00:20:01,480
and you have the domain of the unexpected,

461
00:20:01,560 --> 00:20:04,360
and then you have the border between them as well.

462
00:20:04,746 --> 00:20:05,788
So that's a good way

463
00:20:05,830 --> 00:20:07,832
of conceptualizing the world as such.

464
00:20:07,957 --> 00:20:11,695
And my proposition was that you experience

465
00:20:11,720 --> 00:20:14,600
the positive meaning that lightens up your life

466
00:20:14,629 --> 00:20:16,535
when you're standing on the border

467
00:20:16,560 --> 00:20:17,673
between order and chaos.

468
00:20:17,715 --> 00:20:20,342
That's the border of optimized transformation.

469
00:20:20,480 --> 00:20:22,520
Because you might say you're

470
00:20:23,520 --> 00:20:26,215
best situated when you're firmly

471
00:20:26,240 --> 00:20:28,265
in the domain of what you understand.

472
00:20:28,300 --> 00:20:29,535
That's what people think

473
00:20:29,560 --> 00:20:31,393
when they pursue security.

474
00:20:31,935 --> 00:20:34,095
But the problem with security is that it

475
00:20:34,120 --> 00:20:35,938
has no element of transformation.

476
00:20:36,360 --> 00:20:38,775
And so you don't only want to be where

477
00:20:38,800 --> 00:20:41,443
things are going the way you want them to go.

478
00:20:41,480 --> 00:20:44,015
You want to be where things are going the way you

479
00:20:44,040 --> 00:20:45,446
want them to go,

480
00:20:45,696 --> 00:20:47,735
but where you're changing and things are

481
00:20:47,760 --> 00:20:49,908
changing so that they can get better.

482
00:20:50,160 --> 00:20:51,280
So it's an edge.

483
00:20:51,560 --> 00:20:54,840
You're not in the domain of the predictable.

484
00:20:55,200 --> 00:20:57,695
You have one foot in the domain of the predictable

485
00:20:57,720 --> 00:21:00,375
and another foot in the domain of the unknown,

486
00:21:00,400 --> 00:21:03,169
so that you can make more of yourself

487
00:21:03,520 --> 00:21:05,440
while you're sufficiently safe.

488
00:21:06,440 --> 00:21:07,840
And that's why,

489
00:21:09,960 --> 00:21:12,440
that's what you do when you play, by the way.

490
00:21:13,560 --> 00:21:16,095
When you play, you manifest a set

491
00:21:16,120 --> 00:21:18,160
of skills that you've already mastered.

492
00:21:18,185 --> 00:21:20,434
Otherwise, you don't know how to play the game,

493
00:21:20,475 --> 00:21:22,460
but you want to play the game on the edge.

494
00:21:22,485 --> 00:21:25,215
That's why you pick a partner in a play about,

495
00:21:25,240 --> 00:21:28,399
that's a challenge to you.

496
00:21:28,440 --> 00:21:29,733
Because you might think, well,

497
00:21:29,775 --> 00:21:31,151
if you're playing with someone,

498
00:21:31,193 --> 00:21:33,153
why not just pick someone that you can beat

499
00:21:33,440 --> 00:21:36,113
hands down 100% of the time?

500
00:21:36,680 --> 00:21:39,120
And your answer would be, well, that's no fun.

501
00:21:39,205 --> 00:21:41,455
And the question about that is, well,

502
00:21:41,480 --> 00:21:45,800
why is it no fun if the aim of the game is to win?

503
00:21:45,961 --> 00:21:47,615
Why not pick a partner that you

504
00:21:47,640 --> 00:21:49,360
can beat 100% of the time?

505
00:21:49,800 --> 00:21:50,895
Because then you win.

506
00:21:50,920 --> 00:21:54,254
And the answer is, in the pursuit of that narrow,

507
00:21:54,280 --> 00:21:56,935
certain victory, you forego the possibility

508
00:21:56,960 --> 00:21:59,341
of becoming a better player.

509
00:21:59,800 --> 00:22:00,717
Right. OK.

510
00:22:00,759 --> 00:22:04,135
So there's a meaning in security, which is that

511
00:22:04,160 --> 00:22:06,639
you can predict everything that's going to happen.

512
00:22:06,681 --> 00:22:08,495
And there's a meaning in the unknown,

513
00:22:08,520 --> 00:22:10,240
which is that you're put off your,

514
00:22:10,840 --> 00:22:13,353
what would you say, you're thrown off your feet

515
00:22:13,447 --> 00:22:17,120
and you're surprised and threatened and anxious.

516
00:22:17,189 --> 00:22:19,535
And then there's a meaning on the border between

517
00:22:19,560 --> 00:22:21,693
those where you're secure enough so that you're

518
00:22:21,735 --> 00:22:23,935
stable, but you're transforming enough so

519
00:22:23,960 --> 00:22:25,905
that you're moving towards an optimized

520
00:22:25,947 --> 00:22:27,823
version of yourself and the world.

521
00:22:28,200 --> 00:22:29,922
OK, so what we're going to do

522
00:22:30,200 --> 00:22:33,575
is to detail out the processes by which you

523
00:22:33,600 --> 00:22:35,386
develop the vision that enables

524
00:22:35,413 --> 00:22:37,832
you to stand on that edge.

525
00:22:38,480 --> 00:22:39,541
That's the plan.

526
00:22:39,791 --> 00:22:40,834
All right.

527
00:22:46,839 --> 00:22:49,400
Now, we live in time.

528
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:52,093
We live in space, obviously.

529
00:22:54,053 --> 00:22:55,847
We inhabit our different territories,

530
00:22:55,888 --> 00:22:57,807
but we also live in time.

531
00:22:57,840 --> 00:23:00,975
And the entire expanse of time is also

532
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:02,800
characterized by this relationship

533
00:23:02,825 --> 00:23:04,812
between the known and the unknown.

534
00:23:04,854 --> 00:23:06,292
Here's an example.

535
00:23:07,280 --> 00:23:09,817
You may have memories that come to visit you

536
00:23:09,858 --> 00:23:12,560
of past troubles,

537
00:23:13,632 --> 00:23:16,840
and those will come on you involuntarily.

538
00:23:17,781 --> 00:23:20,200
And when they do, they make you anxious.

539
00:23:20,600 --> 00:23:23,615
They take the foundation out

540
00:23:23,640 --> 00:23:25,140
from underneath your feet.

541
00:23:25,320 --> 00:23:27,495
And the degree to which they do that is

542
00:23:27,520 --> 00:23:30,320
proportionate to how serious the

543
00:23:31,280 --> 00:23:33,920
chasm that you encountered.

544
00:23:34,960 --> 00:23:37,215
It's proportionate to the depth of the chasm

545
00:23:37,240 --> 00:23:38,880
that you encountered in the past.

546
00:23:39,600 --> 00:23:44,160
If you have experiences that hurt you,

547
00:23:44,760 --> 00:23:47,215
that you don't understand and didn't master

548
00:23:47,240 --> 00:23:50,000
and could still disturb you in the future,

549
00:23:50,480 --> 00:23:52,295
then those visions, those visions

550
00:23:52,320 --> 00:23:54,646
of the past will come to haunt you.

551
00:23:54,937 --> 00:23:56,439
They'll haunt your nightmares.

552
00:23:56,467 --> 00:23:58,177
They'll haunt your daydreams.

553
00:23:58,440 --> 00:24:00,012
They'll destabilize you.

554
00:24:00,095 --> 00:24:02,080
You'll be tempted to push them away.

555
00:24:02,440 --> 00:24:03,400
And what that is,

556
00:24:03,960 --> 00:24:06,600
the reason that that happens is because your

557
00:24:06,720 --> 00:24:09,695
psyche is set up so that if you fell into a hole

558
00:24:09,720 --> 00:24:12,280
once and you don't know why,

559
00:24:13,280 --> 00:24:16,495
the more instinctual parts of you are going

560
00:24:16,520 --> 00:24:19,120
to presume that that danger still lurks

561
00:24:19,200 --> 00:24:22,040
in the future and will re-present those

562
00:24:22,160 --> 00:24:26,680
experiences to you in the hope of motivating you

563
00:24:27,080 --> 00:24:31,200
to develop the adaptive competence necessary

564
00:24:31,225 --> 00:24:33,887
so you won't fall into that hole again.

565
00:24:34,440 --> 00:24:37,014
One of the things you do in therapy,

566
00:24:37,431 --> 00:24:38,641
one of the things you do

567
00:24:38,682 --> 00:24:41,101
with your friends and your family members or even

568
00:24:41,143 --> 00:24:43,103
with yourself, if you have some wisdom,

569
00:24:43,144 --> 00:24:44,646
is if someone has a problem,

570
00:24:44,680 --> 00:24:48,375
you try to walk through with them why the problem

571
00:24:48,400 --> 00:24:49,149
emerged,

572
00:24:49,274 --> 00:24:50,817
which might have something to do

573
00:24:50,859 --> 00:24:52,277
with the vagaries of the world,

574
00:24:52,319 --> 00:24:54,153
because things happen to us that are

575
00:24:54,200 --> 00:24:58,000
accidental and random, that are difficult

576
00:24:58,520 --> 00:24:59,658
and dangerous,

577
00:24:59,880 --> 00:25:03,735
but also that our misadventures may have something

578
00:25:03,760 --> 00:25:07,095
to do with the improper calibration of the way

579
00:25:07,120 --> 00:25:09,041
that we're looking at and

580
00:25:09,080 --> 00:25:10,520
interacting with the world.

581
00:25:10,624 --> 00:25:12,520
And so when you're thinking about

582
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:16,040
things that befell you in the past, let's say,

583
00:25:16,800 --> 00:25:19,520
you may have to develop a relatively sophisticated

584
00:25:19,800 --> 00:25:22,335
theory of the randomness of the world and come

585
00:25:22,360 --> 00:25:25,360
to terms with that, but you may also have to

586
00:25:25,960 --> 00:25:29,495
determine as precisely as you can what

587
00:25:29,520 --> 00:25:31,575
insufficiencies you might have brought

588
00:25:31,600 --> 00:25:33,615
to the situation that made you more

589
00:25:33,640 --> 00:25:35,563
vulnerable than you needed to be.

590
00:25:35,840 --> 00:25:38,200
So, for example, if you were bullied as a child,

591
00:25:38,680 --> 00:25:42,535
maybe you still are concerned when you go to your

592
00:25:42,560 --> 00:25:44,821
workplace, for example, especially if it's new,

593
00:25:44,862 --> 00:25:46,840
that the same pattern might recur,

594
00:25:46,920 --> 00:25:49,855
and you might remember with some apprehension

595
00:25:49,880 --> 00:25:52,160
the misadventures you had when you were young.

596
00:25:52,202 --> 00:25:54,960
And what that indicates is that, possibly,

597
00:25:55,280 --> 00:25:56,320
that you haven't

598
00:25:57,240 --> 00:26:00,855
redressed the insufficiencies in your personality

599
00:26:00,880 --> 00:26:02,615
that led you to be the victim

600
00:26:02,640 --> 00:26:03,720
of repeated bullying.

601
00:26:03,837 --> 00:26:06,297
I used bullying as an example because one thing we

602
00:26:06,339 --> 00:26:08,090
do know is that there is some

603
00:26:08,382 --> 00:26:11,535
stability in the probability that a given child

604
00:26:11,560 --> 00:26:14,938
will be a bully or be a victim of bullies.

605
00:26:15,439 --> 00:26:18,015
And so I'm not trying to blame the victim

606
00:26:18,040 --> 00:26:20,152
of a bully for the fact that that happens.

607
00:26:20,517 --> 00:26:22,686
I'm just saying that if negative things have

608
00:26:22,727 --> 00:26:24,562
befallen you in the past,

609
00:26:24,640 --> 00:26:28,335
it's wisdom to determine what it is that you might

610
00:26:28,360 --> 00:26:31,600
be doing wrong that's opening yourself up

611
00:26:31,680 --> 00:26:33,248
to the possibility that those

612
00:26:33,749 --> 00:26:35,695
sorts of things will happen to you.

613
00:26:35,720 --> 00:26:36,695
And I would say,

614
00:26:36,720 --> 00:26:39,920
if you're characterized by patterns of negative

615
00:26:40,560 --> 00:26:44,175
events, then it's reasonably probable

616
00:26:44,200 --> 00:26:46,956
that you're bringing something to the situation.

617
00:26:47,080 --> 00:26:49,720
If it happens to you once, well, it's random.

618
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:52,726
And maybe if it happens to you twice, it's random.

619
00:26:53,227 --> 00:26:55,535
But if it happens, if you have this same sort

620
00:26:55,560 --> 00:26:58,375
of relationship with an intimate

621
00:26:58,400 --> 00:27:01,520
partner three times, it's you.

622
00:27:02,720 --> 00:27:05,535
Right, and that's an uncomfortable thing

623
00:27:05,560 --> 00:27:07,348
to realize, and you can understand

624
00:27:07,560 --> 00:27:09,895
why a stance like that might be criticized

625
00:27:09,920 --> 00:27:11,815
in relationship to blaming the victim.

626
00:27:11,840 --> 00:27:13,440
But look at it this way.

627
00:27:13,680 --> 00:27:15,960
Even if it's 5% you,

628
00:27:16,960 --> 00:27:18,941
maybe you should do something about it.

629
00:27:18,982 --> 00:27:21,109
That's a useful thing to know, by the way,

630
00:27:21,151 --> 00:27:22,280
if you're having

631
00:27:23,360 --> 00:27:26,009
difficult discussions with an intimate partner

632
00:27:26,239 --> 00:27:28,775
that you have now or a family member or a friend.

633
00:27:28,800 --> 00:27:32,695
If you're in a situation where your interactions

634
00:27:32,720 --> 00:27:34,895
aren't proceeding in the manner that you would

635
00:27:34,920 --> 00:27:38,135
find optimal, one thing that's very much worth

636
00:27:38,160 --> 00:27:39,775
doing is trying to figure out what

637
00:27:39,800 --> 00:27:41,376
it is that you're doing wrong.

638
00:27:41,418 --> 00:27:43,086
It's often very difficult, right?

639
00:27:43,128 --> 00:27:45,588
Because if you're in a disagreement with someone,

640
00:27:46,172 --> 00:27:48,549
the part of you that's seeking security is going

641
00:27:48,590 --> 00:27:50,717
to want to insist that, look, we're having

642
00:27:50,759 --> 00:27:54,520
a fight here, but it's at least 95% you.

643
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:56,720
And that's an easy—well,

644
00:27:56,880 --> 00:27:58,695
and anger will make you think that.

645
00:27:58,720 --> 00:28:01,200
Anger will also make you want to win.

646
00:28:01,520 --> 00:28:04,615
The thing is, it might be 90% the other person,

647
00:28:04,640 --> 00:28:06,960
although on average, it's probably not.

648
00:28:07,320 --> 00:28:09,052
But even if it's 10% you,

649
00:28:09,960 --> 00:28:12,681
that's something that is under your control

650
00:28:12,764 --> 00:28:15,800
and you could rectify, and if you did,

651
00:28:16,040 --> 00:28:19,455
might stop the 90% from making itself manifest

652
00:28:19,480 --> 00:28:20,701
in the other person,

653
00:28:20,742 --> 00:28:22,285
because you never know

654
00:28:22,320 --> 00:28:24,329
to what degree your imperfections are

655
00:28:24,370 --> 00:28:26,680
bringing about the conflicts in your life.

656
00:28:27,200 --> 00:28:28,906
Now, you have to be careful to

657
00:28:29,166 --> 00:28:31,585
meditate on that because you don't want to take

658
00:28:31,626 --> 00:28:33,994
yourself apart, but you can learn techniques,

659
00:28:34,240 --> 00:28:35,755
and we'll talk about them, too,

660
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:38,455
so that you don't force upon yourself

661
00:28:38,480 --> 00:28:40,055
the necessity of a transformation

662
00:28:40,080 --> 00:28:42,419
that's so rapid that it undermines you.

663
00:28:42,800 --> 00:28:44,840
If it starts to become too threatening,

664
00:28:45,080 --> 00:28:47,181
if the magnitude of change that you're

665
00:28:47,223 --> 00:28:50,680
apprehending that's necessary for yourself is too

666
00:28:50,851 --> 00:28:54,395
daunting, then you're biting off more than you can

667
00:28:54,437 --> 00:28:58,565
chew and you should try to change slightly slower.

668
00:28:59,102 --> 00:29:00,775
Maybe you should try to change

669
00:29:00,800 --> 00:29:02,480
at the rate that you find optimal.

670
00:29:02,652 --> 00:29:05,029
And that's a good thing to learn about yourself.

671
00:29:05,071 --> 00:29:07,695
If you know that there's something that you have

672
00:29:07,720 --> 00:29:09,640
to do and you're not doing it,

673
00:29:10,200 --> 00:29:12,535
one tactic that you can employ that's

674
00:29:12,577 --> 00:29:15,246
extremely useful is to shrink the task.

675
00:29:15,788 --> 00:29:17,200
So maybe, I don't know,

676
00:29:17,248 --> 00:29:19,666
maybe your garage is a mess and it's been that way

677
00:29:19,706 --> 00:29:21,541
for 10 years and you can't get

678
00:29:21,585 --> 00:29:22,919
yourself in there to clean.

679
00:29:22,961 --> 00:29:24,879
It's like, well, maybe you should clean up

680
00:29:24,920 --> 00:29:28,382
one corner in a week, something like that.

681
00:29:28,882 --> 00:29:31,760
You can shrink the task until you'll find

682
00:29:32,520 --> 00:29:34,804
a step forward that you will take.

683
00:29:35,720 --> 00:29:37,840
And maybe if you're sophisticated,

684
00:29:38,058 --> 00:29:40,015
you could find a step forward that you

685
00:29:40,040 --> 00:29:42,185
would take, that you would take happily.

686
00:29:42,604 --> 00:29:45,135
And this is a good thing to know, too, when you're

687
00:29:45,160 --> 00:29:47,481
negotiating, say, with your wife or your husband.

688
00:29:47,523 --> 00:29:49,640
You want them or you

689
00:29:50,440 --> 00:29:52,444
or the two of you to make a change.

690
00:29:52,480 --> 00:29:56,040
You can negotiate the change until you find

691
00:29:56,239 --> 00:29:58,782
a change that's small enough and interesting

692
00:29:58,824 --> 00:30:00,992
enough so you might both be willing

693
00:30:01,034 --> 00:30:02,869
to experiment with it happily.

694
00:30:03,160 --> 00:30:05,495
And there's a certain humility in that, right?

695
00:30:05,520 --> 00:30:07,456
Because one of the things I noticed

696
00:30:07,498 --> 00:30:09,000
as a clinician often was that,

697
00:30:09,800 --> 00:30:12,300
if my clients were starting to make a positive

698
00:30:12,884 --> 00:30:14,280
change in a new direction,

699
00:30:14,720 --> 00:30:16,975
especially in a domain where they had had some

700
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:18,348
habitual weakness,

701
00:30:18,600 --> 00:30:21,735
they often had to start that change at a level

702
00:30:21,760 --> 00:30:23,775
that was so trivial that it

703
00:30:23,800 --> 00:30:25,175
was embarrassing or shameful.

704
00:30:25,200 --> 00:30:27,400
And so that's where the humility comes in.

705
00:30:27,431 --> 00:30:29,433
There's going to be parts of your personality

706
00:30:29,475 --> 00:30:30,601
that are pretty immature,

707
00:30:30,642 --> 00:30:33,019
and the probability that you have to do something

708
00:30:33,061 --> 00:30:34,575
shamefully small to start

709
00:30:34,600 --> 00:30:36,408
improving that is extremely high.

710
00:30:36,814 --> 00:30:38,800
But one thing to know about that is,

711
00:30:39,566 --> 00:30:40,975
change accelerates.

712
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:43,200
And so even if you have to start slow,

713
00:30:43,440 --> 00:30:45,815
that doesn't mean that that isn't going

714
00:30:45,840 --> 00:30:47,880
to start a process that will accelerate.

715
00:30:48,400 --> 00:30:50,775
And so even if your first steps have to be

716
00:30:50,800 --> 00:30:53,453
embarrassingly tiny, that doesn't mean that you're

717
00:30:53,480 --> 00:30:56,775
destined to only take embarrassingly tiny steps

718
00:30:56,800 --> 00:30:58,735
during the entire process

719
00:30:58,760 --> 00:31:00,657
of necessary transformation.

720
00:31:00,682 --> 00:31:03,135
Carl Jung said, "The fool is

721
00:31:03,160 --> 00:31:05,415
the precursor to the savior."

722
00:31:05,440 --> 00:31:07,055
That's why comedians are

723
00:31:07,080 --> 00:31:08,495
so necessary, by the way.

724
00:31:08,520 --> 00:31:10,300
But what he meant by that was that,

725
00:31:10,342 --> 00:31:12,240
if you want to make a change in a positive

726
00:31:12,265 --> 00:31:13,560
direction, you have to allow

727
00:31:13,585 --> 00:31:15,471
yourself to be a fool to begin with.

728
00:31:15,513 --> 00:31:18,015
You're going to do things stupidly and badly when

729
00:31:18,040 --> 00:31:20,095
you first do them, although maybe slightly

730
00:31:20,120 --> 00:31:22,535
better than you had done them before.

731
00:31:22,560 --> 00:31:24,695
And maybe even stupidly and badly

732
00:31:24,720 --> 00:31:26,564
is better than pure avoidance.

733
00:31:26,856 --> 00:31:29,191
And this is a good thing to know, too, when you're

734
00:31:29,233 --> 00:31:31,443
negotiating again with your husband or your wife.

735
00:31:31,485 --> 00:31:34,360
If there's something that you would want from them

736
00:31:34,404 --> 00:31:37,448
that you think would help you

737
00:31:38,360 --> 00:31:40,951
strengthen your commitment to the relationship,

738
00:31:41,360 --> 00:31:43,203
you can negotiate with them

739
00:31:44,287 --> 00:31:45,788
until you find a small change

740
00:31:45,830 --> 00:31:48,332
that they're willing to do voluntarily,

741
00:31:48,374 --> 00:31:50,709
and you can allow them to do that badly.

742
00:31:51,600 --> 00:31:53,294
This is a very good thing to know,

743
00:31:53,336 --> 00:31:54,880
especially if you're with someone

744
00:31:54,905 --> 00:31:56,860
you're going to be with for a long time.

745
00:31:57,000 --> 00:31:59,280
One of the things I used to do in my clinical

746
00:31:59,400 --> 00:32:01,455
practice was some relationship counseling,

747
00:32:01,480 --> 00:32:02,510
and one of the things

748
00:32:02,552 --> 00:32:03,970
I would recommend to my clients

749
00:32:04,012 --> 00:32:05,638
who were in a long-term relationship

750
00:32:05,680 --> 00:32:08,720
or married was to go on dates with their partner.

751
00:32:09,058 --> 00:32:11,335
And people were often very resistant

752
00:32:11,360 --> 00:32:14,135
to that for all, probably because they tried it

753
00:32:14,160 --> 00:32:16,480
a number of times and been burned in some way,

754
00:32:16,522 --> 00:32:18,941
or they'd say things like, "Well, I don't have

755
00:32:18,982 --> 00:32:20,720
to date because now I'm married."

756
00:32:20,745 --> 00:32:22,320
It's like, OK,

757
00:32:22,611 --> 00:32:25,071
you don't want any romance in your life?

758
00:32:25,113 --> 00:32:26,822
And then they'd go out and have a date,

759
00:32:26,864 --> 00:32:28,490
and they'd come back and tell me about

760
00:32:28,532 --> 00:32:30,117
how wretched and miserable it went.

761
00:32:30,158 --> 00:32:32,015
And then we do a little arithmetic,

762
00:32:32,040 --> 00:32:34,815
which is always a useful thing to do

763
00:32:34,840 --> 00:32:37,039
in a situation like this, let's say.

764
00:32:37,080 --> 00:32:41,495
Maybe you want to have three intimate interactions

765
00:32:41,520 --> 00:32:45,440
with your marital partner a week for 50 years.

766
00:32:45,760 --> 00:32:47,240
Let's say that, or two.

767
00:32:47,640 --> 00:32:48,966
Let's go with three.

768
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:51,880
That's 12 a month or about 150 a year.

769
00:32:52,280 --> 00:32:54,560
And over 50 years, that's 7,500

770
00:32:55,160 --> 00:32:56,880
interactions, 7,500.

771
00:32:57,181 --> 00:32:58,474
OK, maybe you have to do

772
00:32:58,508 --> 00:33:00,392
the first 200 of them badly.

773
00:33:00,880 --> 00:33:02,269
And 200 is a lot,

774
00:33:02,310 --> 00:33:04,687
but it's nothing compared to 7,500.

775
00:33:04,729 --> 00:33:07,760
And so if you're willing to let yourself stumble

776
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:11,360
forward when you're improving things that repeat,

777
00:33:11,800 --> 00:33:14,055
you allow yourself that space for play

778
00:33:14,080 --> 00:33:16,655
and for error, then you can learn to incrementally

779
00:33:16,680 --> 00:33:21,655
master in a manner that enables you

780
00:33:21,680 --> 00:33:23,560
to become a master over the long run.

781
00:33:24,080 --> 00:33:26,077
Another thing to think about that, too,

782
00:33:26,360 --> 00:33:28,975
that it isn't so obvious when you first apprehend

783
00:33:29,000 --> 00:33:31,495
it, is that your life in the main

784
00:33:31,520 --> 00:33:33,670
is made up of things you repeat.

785
00:33:34,200 --> 00:33:38,735
And we tend to downplay the significance of things

786
00:33:38,760 --> 00:33:41,775
that we repeat because they're everyday, right?

787
00:33:41,800 --> 00:33:43,240
They're normal, they're drab.

788
00:33:43,560 --> 00:33:45,640
Coming home from work is a good example.

789
00:33:46,097 --> 00:33:47,681
You're going to come home from work

790
00:33:47,723 --> 00:33:48,849
five days a week.

791
00:33:48,891 --> 00:33:50,434
There's going to be a transition

792
00:33:50,475 --> 00:33:52,135
period from work that's 20 minutes.

793
00:33:52,160 --> 00:33:55,335
And that transition period is going to happen

794
00:33:55,360 --> 00:33:56,856
every day, and it's going to set

795
00:33:56,897 --> 00:33:58,691
the tone for the rest of the day.

796
00:33:58,840 --> 00:34:01,613
And so it's often the case that those transition

797
00:34:01,776 --> 00:34:03,403
periods are awkward for people,

798
00:34:03,445 --> 00:34:05,154
and they don't do anything about it.

799
00:34:05,196 --> 00:34:06,572
And that's a huge mistake.

800
00:34:06,600 --> 00:34:08,699
Because 20 minutes a day—

801
00:34:08,741 --> 00:34:10,534
we can do the arithmetic—

802
00:34:10,575 --> 00:34:14,292
that's 20 minutes a day times three.

803
00:34:15,210 --> 00:34:17,289
So that's 2 hours a week, let's say.

804
00:34:17,320 --> 00:34:18,707
It's 8 hours a month.

805
00:34:20,160 --> 00:34:23,440
So it's 12 work days a year, essentially.

806
00:34:24,240 --> 00:34:26,880
And so that's 5% of your life.

807
00:34:27,920 --> 00:34:29,160
That's 5% of your life.

808
00:34:30,259 --> 00:34:32,344
If you get 20 things like that right,

809
00:34:32,385 --> 00:34:34,304
you have your whole life right.

810
00:34:35,760 --> 00:34:38,375
And so you look at the things that repeat, right?

811
00:34:38,400 --> 00:34:39,440
You master them.

812
00:34:39,683 --> 00:34:41,695
You make incremental progress to making

813
00:34:41,720 --> 00:34:43,780
them as perfect as they can possibly be.

814
00:34:44,200 --> 00:34:45,975
You negotiate with your partner so

815
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:47,523
that that occurs,

816
00:34:47,560 --> 00:34:49,520
and you allow that negotiation to

817
00:34:50,920 --> 00:34:53,280
make itself manifest imperfectly

818
00:34:53,800 --> 00:34:56,360
and in a manner that's ridden with errors

819
00:34:56,680 --> 00:34:58,615
so that you can continually correct it.

820
00:34:58,640 --> 00:35:00,400
And hopefully, after you repeat it

821
00:35:00,840 --> 00:35:02,800
100 times, you get it right.

822
00:35:03,280 --> 00:35:04,775
And you do that 20 times,

823
00:35:04,800 --> 00:35:06,560
and everything in your life is set,

824
00:35:06,970 --> 00:35:09,815
not only in order, but in the order

825
00:35:09,840 --> 00:35:11,455
that's on the edge of play.

826
00:35:11,480 --> 00:35:12,043
Right.

827
00:35:12,080 --> 00:35:13,086
And you can do that.

828
00:35:13,128 --> 00:35:14,671
You have to think about it, though.

829
00:35:14,712 --> 00:35:15,922
You have to think about—

830
00:35:15,963 --> 00:35:18,090
I see this with parents and their children.

831
00:35:18,132 --> 00:35:20,095
You'll have someone with a two-year-old,

832
00:35:20,120 --> 00:35:22,235
and every bedtime's a fight.

833
00:35:23,120 --> 00:35:25,320
Well, you got to think that through, because

834
00:35:25,880 --> 00:35:28,967
parents actually only spend about 20 minutes

835
00:35:28,992 --> 00:35:32,280
a day in one-on-one interaction with their kids.

836
00:35:32,769 --> 00:35:34,375
It's a much smaller fraction

837
00:35:34,400 --> 00:35:35,855
of your time than you think.

838
00:35:36,200 --> 00:35:40,375
And if that interaction is bedtime and every night

839
00:35:40,400 --> 00:35:43,403
it's a misery, then what you've done is,

840
00:35:43,445 --> 00:35:45,822
you've made that whole relationship into misery.

841
00:35:45,863 --> 00:35:46,840
And you think, well,

842
00:35:46,865 --> 00:35:48,655
it's only when I put my kid to bed.

843
00:35:48,680 --> 00:35:49,950
It's like, no, it's not only that

844
00:35:49,992 --> 00:35:51,952
because it happens every day.

845
00:35:52,080 --> 00:35:54,935
And if that sets the pattern of your relationship,

846
00:35:54,960 --> 00:35:57,975
that it's nothing but strife and foolish conflict,

847
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:00,615
then, well, how are you going to establish a good

848
00:36:00,640 --> 00:36:03,080
relationship with your child and vice versa?

849
00:36:03,320 --> 00:36:05,153
All they are is a problem to you.

850
00:36:06,130 --> 00:36:07,575
And that's not a good thing.

851
00:36:07,600 --> 00:36:10,742
And so, pay attention to the things that repeat.

852
00:36:11,242 --> 00:36:12,719
They're very, very important.

853
00:36:12,760 --> 00:36:13,928
That's your life.

854
00:36:14,160 --> 00:36:17,375
People get obsessed about the exceptions,

855
00:36:17,400 --> 00:36:19,455
vacations, the special occasions in their life.

856
00:36:19,480 --> 00:36:21,690
And those are often a disappointment, by the way.

857
00:36:21,720 --> 00:36:23,680
And that's fair enough because,

858
00:36:24,080 --> 00:36:26,095
well, it's because people overvalue them,

859
00:36:26,120 --> 00:36:27,940
and then they go have the experience

860
00:36:27,982 --> 00:36:29,483
and it doesn't meet their expectations.

861
00:36:29,525 --> 00:36:31,040
And so then they're miserable while they

862
00:36:31,065 --> 00:36:32,861
have it and they have nothing but regret.

863
00:36:32,902 --> 00:36:34,404
And part of the problem with that,

864
00:36:34,445 --> 00:36:36,015
part of what's causing that,

865
00:36:36,040 --> 00:36:38,960
is that they're paying way too much attention

866
00:36:39,120 --> 00:36:41,495
to what's hypothetically exceptional and not

867
00:36:41,520 --> 00:36:42,952
nearly enough attention

868
00:36:42,994 --> 00:36:45,615
to what is normal and repeats.

869
00:36:45,640 --> 00:36:47,495
And that's a form of pride, too,

870
00:36:47,520 --> 00:36:50,655
because you might want to identify with only

871
00:36:50,680 --> 00:36:52,836
the things in your life that are exceptional

872
00:36:52,877 --> 00:36:55,215
and not the boring and drab day-to-day

873
00:36:55,240 --> 00:36:56,880
things that you do all the time.

874
00:36:57,247 --> 00:36:59,480
But you could elevate those

875
00:37:00,040 --> 00:37:03,320
to the point of some optimized perfection.

876
00:37:03,345 --> 00:37:05,471
You could tell you're doing that, by the way,

877
00:37:05,513 --> 00:37:07,807
because you can do it in a state of play.

878
00:37:08,224 --> 00:37:10,309
And that's also a very good thing to know.

879
00:37:10,350 --> 00:37:12,200
It took me a long time to figure this out.

880
00:37:12,225 --> 00:37:15,375
I spent decades trying to understand what

881
00:37:15,400 --> 00:37:18,440
the opposite of tyrannical power was.

882
00:37:18,732 --> 00:37:20,734
It's not an easy thing to conceptualize,

883
00:37:20,776 --> 00:37:22,655
but I believe that it's play.

884
00:37:22,680 --> 00:37:24,855
And I think that you know if you have

885
00:37:24,880 --> 00:37:27,800
a situation mastered if you can do it playfully.

886
00:37:27,825 --> 00:37:30,033
Imagine the situation where you're trying to put

887
00:37:30,071 --> 00:37:31,535
your little kid to bed,

888
00:37:31,960 --> 00:37:34,200
and that turns into a bout of play.

889
00:37:34,621 --> 00:37:36,535
Well, then you've got it, and then you

890
00:37:36,580 --> 00:37:38,290
do nothing but look forward to that.

891
00:37:38,320 --> 00:37:39,791
And that would be a good deal.

892
00:37:39,833 --> 00:37:42,127
If you were in a situation where you could do

893
00:37:42,480 --> 00:37:45,135
nothing but look forward to the things you repeat

894
00:37:45,160 --> 00:37:47,335
every day, that'd be a good

895
00:37:47,360 --> 00:37:49,091
bargain to strike with yourself.

896
00:37:49,280 --> 00:37:51,895
And it's also something to consider, too.

897
00:37:51,920 --> 00:37:55,015
If you have things you're doing every day that you

898
00:37:55,040 --> 00:37:58,599
dread, well, one question you might ask is,

899
00:37:58,641 --> 00:38:00,495
is there something wrong with your attitude?

900
00:38:00,520 --> 00:38:01,495
Because maybe there is,

901
00:38:01,520 --> 00:38:03,320
and you should dig into that and find out.

902
00:38:03,345 --> 00:38:05,535
But another conclusion you might draw is

903
00:38:05,560 --> 00:38:07,620
maybe you're not doing the right thing.

904
00:38:07,920 --> 00:38:10,095
And then you have to strategize carefully,

905
00:38:10,120 --> 00:38:11,860
and that has to do with the development

906
00:38:11,902 --> 00:38:14,115
of a vision, about maybe you hate your job.

907
00:38:15,783 --> 00:38:18,135
And you think, well, I have to have this job

908
00:38:18,160 --> 00:38:20,560
because I have to take care of my family.

909
00:38:20,826 --> 00:38:23,280
That's a tyrannical attitude all the way through.

910
00:38:23,305 --> 00:38:25,040
And you're blaming your family,

911
00:38:25,440 --> 00:38:27,289
so that's a real good deal for them.

912
00:38:27,520 --> 00:38:30,135
They're now the shackles that keep you

913
00:38:30,160 --> 00:38:32,960
in slavery to a tyrannical job that you hate.

914
00:38:33,320 --> 00:38:34,671
That's a lovely gift to lay

915
00:38:34,712 --> 00:38:36,055
at the feet of your family.

916
00:38:36,080 --> 00:38:37,572
There's a fair bit of pleasure

917
00:38:37,597 --> 00:38:39,000
of martyrdom in that, too.

918
00:38:39,516 --> 00:38:41,500
And you might say instead, and this is

919
00:38:41,525 --> 00:38:42,615
what you can do, too,

920
00:38:42,640 --> 00:38:45,215
if you're trying to understand the obstacles

921
00:38:45,240 --> 00:38:47,290
that are getting in your way as you progress

922
00:38:47,315 --> 00:38:49,760
is well, why are you stuck with this damn job?

923
00:38:50,267 --> 00:38:52,435
And you got to think about that in detail.

924
00:38:52,477 --> 00:38:53,770
I had clients, for example,

925
00:38:53,812 --> 00:38:55,146
who were stuck in miserable jobs,

926
00:38:55,188 --> 00:38:56,320
and I'd say to them, "Well,

927
00:38:56,345 --> 00:38:59,566
let's take a look at your resume, your CV.

928
00:38:59,608 --> 00:39:00,567
Bring it in next week."

929
00:39:00,609 --> 00:39:01,650
And then they wouldn't.

930
00:39:01,680 --> 00:39:03,000
Then I'd have to find out why.

931
00:39:03,025 --> 00:39:04,815
It's like, well, why do you not

932
00:39:04,840 --> 00:39:06,520
want to show your CV to someone?

933
00:39:06,960 --> 00:39:08,255
Well, here's some reasons.

934
00:39:08,280 --> 00:39:10,575
You haven't updated it for 10 years.

935
00:39:10,880 --> 00:39:13,161
OK, so then, that's kind of daunting, right?

936
00:39:13,203 --> 00:39:14,454
Because it's actually, like,

937
00:39:14,495 --> 00:39:15,705
just because it's difficult,

938
00:39:15,746 --> 00:39:18,015
you have to sit down and go through your life

939
00:39:18,040 --> 00:39:19,208
and you have to structure

940
00:39:19,249 --> 00:39:20,959
that in a way that's comprehensible.

941
00:39:21,000 --> 00:39:23,000
But then, too, the problem with the CV is,

942
00:39:23,044 --> 00:39:24,535
you have to reveal everything

943
00:39:24,560 --> 00:39:26,088
about you that's embarrassing.

944
00:39:26,120 --> 00:39:28,655
Maybe you have to paper over various aspects

945
00:39:28,680 --> 00:39:30,634
of your stupidity with lies,

946
00:39:30,817 --> 00:39:33,575
and that undermines your confidence about the CV

947
00:39:33,600 --> 00:39:34,971
and about the job,

948
00:39:35,400 --> 00:39:37,973
say, the job interview process,

949
00:39:38,015 --> 00:39:40,326
because you have holes in your past

950
00:39:40,351 --> 00:39:42,185
that you don't know what to do with.

951
00:39:42,227 --> 00:39:44,480
Well, you face that.

952
00:39:44,560 --> 00:39:46,855
You think, OK, well—you know, I had clients,

953
00:39:46,880 --> 00:39:49,335
for example, they had 95% of their

954
00:39:49,360 --> 00:39:51,921
undergraduate degree, and then they stopped.

955
00:39:52,360 --> 00:39:54,028
And there's a reason for that.

956
00:39:54,070 --> 00:39:54,737
I don't know.

957
00:39:54,779 --> 00:39:56,739
Maybe they didn't want the responsibility that

958
00:39:56,781 --> 00:39:58,782
would be attendant upon completing the degree.

959
00:39:58,824 --> 00:40:00,909
Maybe it was a good way of getting back at their

960
00:40:00,951 --> 00:40:03,161
father who forced them to go into engineering

961
00:40:03,200 --> 00:40:04,787
when they wanted to be an artist.

962
00:40:04,829 --> 00:40:08,615
There's some reason you stop with it 95% done.

963
00:40:08,640 --> 00:40:10,215
And then you have to fix that because

964
00:40:10,240 --> 00:40:11,775
otherwise you're embarrassed about it.

965
00:40:11,800 --> 00:40:13,211
And if you're embarrassed about it,

966
00:40:13,253 --> 00:40:14,796
then you're not going to be confident

967
00:40:14,837 --> 00:40:16,375
when you go to your job interview.

968
00:40:16,400 --> 00:40:18,455
And if you're afraid of not being confident,

969
00:40:18,480 --> 00:40:19,695
you won't look for a job.

970
00:40:19,720 --> 00:40:21,134
And then if you won't look for a job,

971
00:40:21,176 --> 00:40:22,385
you'll blame your wife because

972
00:40:22,427 --> 00:40:24,012
you have to be tyrannized at work.

973
00:40:24,037 --> 00:40:25,580
That's a stupid game.

974
00:40:25,605 --> 00:40:27,840
And so instead of that, you might figure out,

975
00:40:27,865 --> 00:40:29,933
well, why the hell did you quit when you

976
00:40:29,975 --> 00:40:35,040
were within grasping distance of the goal?

977
00:40:35,560 --> 00:40:37,648
And god only knows why that is,

978
00:40:37,690 --> 00:40:40,234
but maybe it's something that isn't even

979
00:40:40,275 --> 00:40:42,569
true of you anymore.

980
00:40:42,600 --> 00:40:44,935
Maybe you outgrew whatever stupidity

981
00:40:44,960 --> 00:40:47,281
had made you do that 10 years ago.

982
00:40:47,531 --> 00:40:49,015
To put your CV together,

983
00:40:49,040 --> 00:40:50,534
you have to put your past together.

984
00:40:50,575 --> 00:40:52,535
And maybe that takes two years.

985
00:40:52,577 --> 00:40:54,775
If you want to find a job you actually like,

986
00:40:54,800 --> 00:40:57,360
two years isn't too much of an investment to make.

987
00:40:57,385 --> 00:40:59,708
And maybe you're terrified because you're going

988
00:40:59,750 --> 00:41:01,460
to throw your CV out in the wind and

989
00:41:01,501 --> 00:41:04,295
49 out of 50 times it's going to be rejected.

990
00:41:04,337 --> 00:41:06,255
But then you could look at it actuarily

991
00:41:06,297 --> 00:41:08,560
and presume, well, of course that's the case,

992
00:41:08,800 --> 00:41:11,255
because lots of companies advertise positions

993
00:41:11,280 --> 00:41:13,815
that don't even exist because they want to keep

994
00:41:13,840 --> 00:41:16,547
a continual flow of CVs going through the system,

995
00:41:17,131 --> 00:41:19,295
or they advertise because they're required

996
00:41:19,320 --> 00:41:22,440
to legally and they already have a candidate,

997
00:41:22,720 --> 00:41:25,735
or it could be that, at this particular moment,

998
00:41:25,760 --> 00:41:28,175
you're not the best candidate for that particular—

999
00:41:28,200 --> 00:41:29,600
there are a lot of reasons

1000
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:32,235
why you're not going to get the job,

1001
00:41:32,277 --> 00:41:34,320
but they're true for virtually everyone.

1002
00:41:34,345 --> 00:41:36,935
And when you know that the base rate for CV

1003
00:41:36,960 --> 00:41:40,720
submission failure is 95%,

1004
00:41:40,745 --> 00:41:42,661
then you don't have to take it personally.

1005
00:41:42,705 --> 00:41:45,015
And you can think, "Well, I need a new job.

1006
00:41:45,040 --> 00:41:46,747
OK, I have to send out."

1007
00:41:47,206 --> 00:41:49,291
Well, you ask yourself, how many bloody

1008
00:41:49,333 --> 00:41:52,085
resumes can you stand to send out a week?

1009
00:41:52,127 --> 00:41:53,878
And that's a serious question, right?

1010
00:41:53,920 --> 00:41:55,963
How much disappointment can you take?

1011
00:41:56,005 --> 00:41:57,840
I don't know. Maybe you can handle 20

1012
00:41:57,882 --> 00:41:59,591
and maybe you can handle 5.

1013
00:41:59,633 --> 00:42:02,093
There's going to be some individual difference in

1014
00:42:02,135 --> 00:42:05,138
that, but you could consult yourself and find out.

1015
00:42:05,263 --> 00:42:07,014
And maybe you're so afraid to begin

1016
00:42:07,056 --> 00:42:08,682
with that you can only send out one.

1017
00:42:08,724 --> 00:42:10,475
It's like, one is a lot more than zero.

1018
00:42:10,517 --> 00:42:12,135
And once you've done one,

1019
00:42:12,160 --> 00:42:13,695
well, maybe you could do three.

1020
00:42:13,720 --> 00:42:16,080
And once you did three, maybe you could do 10.

1021
00:42:16,360 --> 00:42:18,482
And you could settle on, I'll send out—

1022
00:42:18,524 --> 00:42:20,495
you make a routine out of it.

1023
00:42:20,520 --> 00:42:24,480
I'll send out 10 resumes a week for, like, a year.

1024
00:42:25,321 --> 00:42:27,695
And if you do that, if you've updated your CV

1025
00:42:27,720 --> 00:42:30,935
and you're aiming at jobs that are hypothetically

1026
00:42:30,960 --> 00:42:34,015
within your purview, and you have a good story

1027
00:42:34,040 --> 00:42:35,913
to tell about why you would be the right

1028
00:42:35,955 --> 00:42:37,915
candidate, and you can figure that out, too.

1029
00:42:37,960 --> 00:42:39,575
If you have a good story to tell,

1030
00:42:39,600 --> 00:42:42,120
you're not going to be nervous about telling it.

1031
00:42:42,294 --> 00:42:43,980
So you got to ask yourself, well,

1032
00:42:44,005 --> 00:42:46,464
why should someone hire you?

1033
00:42:46,631 --> 00:42:49,055
And then you've got to discuss that with someone,

1034
00:42:49,080 --> 00:42:51,655
your wife or friends, and have them hammer away

1035
00:42:51,680 --> 00:42:54,775
at you until you know what you have to offer.

1036
00:42:54,800 --> 00:42:56,895
And then you can go in there with a bit

1037
00:42:56,920 --> 00:42:58,474
of confidence and you can say,

1038
00:42:58,515 --> 00:42:59,850
"Well, I don't know much.

1039
00:43:00,080 --> 00:43:02,895
I don't have any experience in this realm,

1040
00:43:02,920 --> 00:43:04,979
but here's a bunch of things that I've done.

1041
00:43:05,021 --> 00:43:06,575
And here's the investigations

1042
00:43:06,600 --> 00:43:08,399
that I've made about your company.

1043
00:43:08,440 --> 00:43:10,935
And this is why I think I'd be a good fit,

1044
00:43:10,960 --> 00:43:13,120
and this is what I can offer to you.

1045
00:43:13,520 --> 00:43:16,415
And I won't be a catastrophe," which is the one

1046
00:43:16,440 --> 00:43:18,760
thing everyone hiring really wants to know.

1047
00:43:19,120 --> 00:43:20,826
It's like, what do you think?

1048
00:43:20,867 --> 00:43:21,993
Can we do this together?

1049
00:43:22,035 --> 00:43:23,620
And if you have an attitude like that,

1050
00:43:23,661 --> 00:43:24,871
and you do get an interview,

1051
00:43:24,912 --> 00:43:27,575
which you will eventually, then the probability

1052
00:43:27,600 --> 00:43:30,156
that you'll get the job has gone up substantively.

1053
00:43:30,181 --> 00:43:32,720
And so you don't have to stay in your damn rut,

1054
00:43:32,800 --> 00:43:35,935
but you do have to figure out what elements

1055
00:43:35,960 --> 00:43:38,335
of what you don't understand, that chaos

1056
00:43:38,360 --> 00:43:41,280
and potential, are terrifying you into paralysis.

1057
00:43:42,302 --> 00:43:44,320
And then you think, "Well, I'm terrified

1058
00:43:44,345 --> 00:43:45,876
into paralysis by the magnitude

1059
00:43:45,901 --> 00:43:46,815
of the job search."

1060
00:43:46,840 --> 00:43:48,800
It's like, fair enough.

1061
00:43:48,825 --> 00:43:51,135
You may have lots of things

1062
00:43:51,160 --> 00:43:52,560
that you have to put right.

1063
00:43:53,000 --> 00:43:54,415
Make a list of all the things

1064
00:43:54,440 --> 00:43:55,605
that frighten you, right?

1065
00:43:55,646 --> 00:43:57,231
Maybe it's 15 things.

1066
00:43:57,273 --> 00:43:58,855
Then you can rank-order the list.

1067
00:43:58,880 --> 00:44:00,359
This frightens me the least.

1068
00:44:00,400 --> 00:44:01,860
Maybe I could try it.

1069
00:44:01,902 --> 00:44:03,975
And if all of the things frighten you too

1070
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:06,489
much so you're paralyzed, break them down.

1071
00:44:07,120 --> 00:44:11,264
When I was counseling my clients to go on the job

1072
00:44:11,764 --> 00:44:15,080
search, one of their first assignments was often

1073
00:44:16,280 --> 00:44:20,375
"just open up your CV and look at it."

1074
00:44:20,400 --> 00:44:22,415
And this was an actual contract,

1075
00:44:22,440 --> 00:44:24,045
because when you're playing this game

1076
00:44:24,087 --> 00:44:26,339
with yourself, let's say, you can't cheat.

1077
00:44:26,487 --> 00:44:28,880
If you're terrified to go on the job search

1078
00:44:29,280 --> 00:44:32,118
and you've motivated yourself enough

1079
00:44:32,618 --> 00:44:35,175
so that you're willing to open your damn computer

1080
00:44:35,200 --> 00:44:37,455
and look through your CV, don't sit

1081
00:44:37,480 --> 00:44:39,558
down right then and start rewriting it.

1082
00:44:39,600 --> 00:44:41,455
It's a violation of the contract.

1083
00:44:41,480 --> 00:44:43,255
You're pushing yourself too hard.

1084
00:44:43,280 --> 00:44:45,146
What you should do instead is give yourself

1085
00:44:45,188 --> 00:44:47,398
a little pat in the back and say, "You know,

1086
00:44:47,425 --> 00:44:50,360
sad as it is, I was terrified to do this,

1087
00:44:51,280 --> 00:44:52,485
but I did it."

1088
00:44:52,861 --> 00:44:54,904
Right. So it's time to, like—

1089
00:44:54,946 --> 00:44:57,015
if you have a child and the child does

1090
00:44:57,040 --> 00:44:59,415
something new, you're not going to say to them,

1091
00:44:59,440 --> 00:45:00,492
if you have any sense,

1092
00:45:00,534 --> 00:45:02,327
"Why didn't you do twice as much?"

1093
00:45:02,369 --> 00:45:04,840
That's a great way to demoralize someone.

1094
00:45:04,871 --> 00:45:06,895
You also shouldn't do that to yourself.

1095
00:45:06,920 --> 00:45:09,400
If you've taken a step forward, like,

1096
00:45:10,000 --> 00:45:11,495
have a little recognition,

1097
00:45:11,520 --> 00:45:13,495
and maybe you've got someone around you,

1098
00:45:13,520 --> 00:45:16,175
if you're lucky, that you could tell what

1099
00:45:16,200 --> 00:45:19,360
you did to, and they would be happy about it.

1100
00:45:19,440 --> 00:45:21,615
And that's how you distinguish, by the way,

1101
00:45:21,640 --> 00:45:23,136
between the people you should have

1102
00:45:23,178 --> 00:45:25,013
around you and the people you shouldn't.

1103
00:45:25,040 --> 00:45:26,889
Because if you have people around you,

1104
00:45:26,920 --> 00:45:28,840
and you tell them that you made a small step

1105
00:45:28,865 --> 00:45:32,255
forward, and they make light of it or are cynical

1106
00:45:32,280 --> 00:45:34,729
about it or punish you for it,

1107
00:45:34,760 --> 00:45:36,735
you might think very hard about just who it

1108
00:45:36,760 --> 00:45:38,260
is that you're hanging around.

1109
00:45:38,320 --> 00:45:40,695
Because you want to be with people who note your

1110
00:45:40,720 --> 00:45:42,152
progress forward

1111
00:45:42,200 --> 00:45:44,941
and at least don't get in the way.

1112
00:45:45,960 --> 00:45:48,160
And that includes yourself, that's for sure.

1113
00:45:48,444 --> 00:45:48,980
All right.

1114
00:45:49,445 --> 00:45:52,095
So there may be some cleaning up

1115
00:45:52,120 --> 00:45:54,720
of the chaos in your past you have to do.

1116
00:45:55,400 --> 00:45:56,760
And you can note that.

1117
00:45:57,160 --> 00:46:00,480
Imagine you have a goal, getting a new job, and

1118
00:46:01,457 --> 00:46:03,920
you see that there are obstacles in your path

1119
00:46:04,295 --> 00:46:06,547
that are preventing you from moving forward.

1120
00:46:06,589 --> 00:46:08,160
And then you see that some of those

1121
00:46:08,185 --> 00:46:10,384
obstacles have to do with the past.

1122
00:46:10,840 --> 00:46:11,760
Well, so then

1123
00:46:12,552 --> 00:46:14,971
you have to clean up the past to the point where

1124
00:46:15,013 --> 00:46:16,931
those obstacles disappear, and then you

1125
00:46:16,973 --> 00:46:19,975
may find some obstacles in the present.

1126
00:46:20,480 --> 00:46:23,144
Maybe you don't think you're good at interviews.

1127
00:46:23,560 --> 00:46:26,107
Lots of people feel that way.

1128
00:46:26,147 --> 00:46:27,800
Well, then you have to practice that.

1129
00:46:27,825 --> 00:46:29,895
That's a present problem, let's say.

1130
00:46:29,920 --> 00:46:31,985
And although it may have its roots in the past,

1131
00:46:32,027 --> 00:46:34,028
maybe you're not sophisticated enough to conduct

1132
00:46:34,070 --> 00:46:35,488
yourself well in a job interview,

1133
00:46:35,530 --> 00:46:37,239
but that's something you can learn.

1134
00:46:37,280 --> 00:46:39,241
Write down 40 questions that you

1135
00:46:39,280 --> 00:46:40,951
think you might be asked.

1136
00:46:41,560 --> 00:46:44,454
Come up with an answer, not a lie, but an answer.

1137
00:46:44,495 --> 00:46:46,000
Here's the problem with lying.

1138
00:46:47,040 --> 00:46:48,960
Let's say you lie your way into a job.

1139
00:46:49,360 --> 00:46:51,480
Well, then you didn't get the job.

1140
00:46:52,240 --> 00:46:53,801
The lie got the job.

1141
00:46:53,884 --> 00:46:56,120
And if you had to lie to get the job,

1142
00:46:56,720 --> 00:46:58,800
probably it's not the job for you.

1143
00:46:59,360 --> 00:47:01,560
So then your reward is that you get a job

1144
00:47:02,400 --> 00:47:04,887
that isn't for you and that you don't deserve.

1145
00:47:04,920 --> 00:47:07,120
Well, that's a hell of a way to start a job.

1146
00:47:07,440 --> 00:47:10,175
Why don't you start a job that is for you,

1147
00:47:10,200 --> 00:47:12,760
that you do deserve, that you could do.

1148
00:47:13,320 --> 00:47:14,979
That'd be a lot better plan.

1149
00:47:15,063 --> 00:47:16,897
And you might say, well, I have to get

1150
00:47:16,939 --> 00:47:19,108
a pretty dismal job given my qualifications.

1151
00:47:19,149 --> 00:47:21,240
It's like, you start where you are

1152
00:47:22,320 --> 00:47:23,748
or you start on a falsehood.

1153
00:47:24,248 --> 00:47:25,360
And one of the things,

1154
00:47:25,680 --> 00:47:27,490
there's this phenomenon in economics

1155
00:47:27,520 --> 00:47:29,324
called the Matthew principle, by the way.

1156
00:47:29,366 --> 00:47:31,034
And the Matthew principle is,

1157
00:47:31,320 --> 00:47:34,037
"To those who have everything, more will be given.

1158
00:47:34,078 --> 00:47:35,575
And from those who have nothing,

1159
00:47:35,600 --> 00:47:37,206
everything will be taken."

1160
00:47:37,248 --> 00:47:39,455
And this is a reflection of a phenomenon called

1161
00:47:39,480 --> 00:47:40,709
the Pareto distribution.

1162
00:47:40,751 --> 00:47:43,044
And the Pareto distribution works like this:

1163
00:47:43,253 --> 00:47:44,880
progress is not linear.

1164
00:47:45,560 --> 00:47:47,320
It's geometric or exponential.

1165
00:47:47,720 --> 00:47:51,695
Once you start accruing money, the probability

1166
00:47:51,720 --> 00:47:53,919
that you'll accrue more starts to increase.

1167
00:47:53,944 --> 00:47:55,600
This is why a very small percentage

1168
00:47:55,638 --> 00:47:57,515
of the people have all the money.

1169
00:47:57,807 --> 00:48:00,225
If you have a million, it's hard to make—

1170
00:48:00,267 --> 00:48:02,560
if you have no money, it's hard to make a dollar.

1171
00:48:02,602 --> 00:48:04,775
If you have a million, it's a lot easier to make

1172
00:48:04,800 --> 00:48:06,655
the next million than it is

1173
00:48:06,680 --> 00:48:07,857
to make the first million.

1174
00:48:07,898 --> 00:48:09,441
And that continues.

1175
00:48:10,280 --> 00:48:12,295
If you have 400 million, it's a lot

1176
00:48:12,320 --> 00:48:14,120
easier to make a billion, et cetera.

1177
00:48:14,173 --> 00:48:15,415
This is true, by the way,

1178
00:48:15,440 --> 00:48:17,490
for every domain of accomplishment.

1179
00:48:17,531 --> 00:48:20,480
Once you've recorded one album,

1180
00:48:20,920 --> 00:48:22,800
it's much easier to record the next

1181
00:48:22,827 --> 00:48:24,520
than it was to record the first.

1182
00:48:24,880 --> 00:48:27,120
And the third is even easier than the second.

1183
00:48:27,520 --> 00:48:29,160
Success builds upon itself.

1184
00:48:29,600 --> 00:48:30,917
And so what that means,

1185
00:48:31,043 --> 00:48:32,711
and this is a good thing to know,

1186
00:48:32,752 --> 00:48:35,320
as I said before, even if you have to start slow,

1187
00:48:36,280 --> 00:48:38,465
that doesn't mean you're doomed to slow.

1188
00:48:38,507 --> 00:48:39,716
And even if you have to take

1189
00:48:39,758 --> 00:48:41,468
a job that's beneath you—

1190
00:48:41,510 --> 00:48:43,455
which is not a good way of conceptualizing it,

1191
00:48:43,480 --> 00:48:45,655
by the way; if it's actually matched to your

1192
00:48:45,680 --> 00:48:47,932
talents, you should be grateful for it—

1193
00:48:47,973 --> 00:48:50,835
if you do a stellar job at that job,

1194
00:48:50,918 --> 00:48:52,975
the probability that someone will notice

1195
00:48:53,000 --> 00:48:55,188
and push you along is extremely high.

1196
00:48:55,640 --> 00:48:57,857
This is something also that people who are

1197
00:48:57,898 --> 00:49:00,040
bitter and hold back don't understand.

1198
00:49:00,560 --> 00:49:03,215
I used to get undergraduates come to work with me

1199
00:49:03,240 --> 00:49:06,615
in my lab, and I had a lot fewer positions than

1200
00:49:06,640 --> 00:49:09,200
there were inquiring undergraduates, right?

1201
00:49:09,241 --> 00:49:10,980
So they were high-demand positions.

1202
00:49:11,005 --> 00:49:13,161
And generally, what I would do was give

1203
00:49:13,440 --> 00:49:15,360
the undergraduate who's asking a task,

1204
00:49:15,760 --> 00:49:18,295
a real one, because I'd have some—maybe I needed

1205
00:49:18,320 --> 00:49:20,334
them to go investigate some psychological

1206
00:49:20,375 --> 00:49:22,455
phenomenon, make me a little report about it,

1207
00:49:22,480 --> 00:49:24,960
a research review, and I'd give them that

1208
00:49:26,240 --> 00:49:28,549
obligation or opportunity.

1209
00:49:29,623 --> 00:49:33,695
Well, if you are talking with someone who has

1210
00:49:33,720 --> 00:49:37,098
resources that you might want access to,

1211
00:49:37,139 --> 00:49:39,141
if they ask you to do something,

1212
00:49:39,183 --> 00:49:40,840
that's not an obligation.

1213
00:49:41,400 --> 00:49:42,602
That's an opportunity.

1214
00:49:42,644 --> 00:49:44,145
And if you have the two things

1215
00:49:44,187 --> 00:49:45,840
confused, you're doomed.

1216
00:49:47,731 --> 00:49:49,478
If you regard the things that will

1217
00:49:49,503 --> 00:49:51,600
move you forward as an obligation,

1218
00:49:52,152 --> 00:49:54,500
how in the world are you going to move forward?

1219
00:49:54,529 --> 00:49:56,072
So what would happen inevitably

1220
00:49:56,113 --> 00:49:58,032
is that some of the undergraduates would go

1221
00:49:58,073 --> 00:49:59,533
and do just a stellar job,

1222
00:49:59,575 --> 00:50:01,243
and it would be done in two days.

1223
00:50:01,363 --> 00:50:05,295
And then others would come back to me a week later

1224
00:50:05,320 --> 00:50:07,280
and say, "Well, all these things

1225
00:50:07,400 --> 00:50:09,280
came up and I couldn't do it."

1226
00:50:09,622 --> 00:50:12,560
And often the story was very plausible,

1227
00:50:12,585 --> 00:50:14,128
because they had family trouble.

1228
00:50:14,170 --> 00:50:15,963
I don't know what the hell the problem was.

1229
00:50:16,005 --> 00:50:17,655
It was some real problem, or maybe not,

1230
00:50:17,680 --> 00:50:19,800
but at least it sounded like a real problem.

1231
00:50:19,842 --> 00:50:22,344
But then I'd go ask the people who did it,

1232
00:50:23,360 --> 00:50:24,762
who actually did the job,

1233
00:50:24,800 --> 00:50:26,681
and they had just as many problems.

1234
00:50:26,972 --> 00:50:28,557
They just didn't let the problem

1235
00:50:28,599 --> 00:50:30,455
stop them from doing the job.

1236
00:50:30,480 --> 00:50:33,295
And so then I would hire the undergraduates

1237
00:50:33,320 --> 00:50:35,895
who actually did the job and not hire

1238
00:50:35,920 --> 00:50:37,606
the undergraduates who didn't do the job.

1239
00:50:37,648 --> 00:50:39,233
And you might say, "Well, that's pretty

1240
00:50:39,274 --> 00:50:41,401
mean because those poor people had problems."

1241
00:50:41,443 --> 00:50:44,237
It's like, well, maybe they had problems,

1242
00:50:44,280 --> 00:50:45,920
and maybe they were a problem.

1243
00:50:46,155 --> 00:50:48,449
And one of the things I noticed was that if I

1244
00:50:48,490 --> 00:50:50,158
pulled people into my lab who were

1245
00:50:50,200 --> 00:50:52,200
a problem, that was a problem.

1246
00:50:52,702 --> 00:50:54,095
And it wasn't just a problem

1247
00:50:54,120 --> 00:50:55,246
that I had to deal with.

1248
00:50:55,288 --> 00:50:57,775
It was a problem that often infected the entire

1249
00:50:57,800 --> 00:51:00,375
lab and especially demoralized

1250
00:51:00,400 --> 00:51:02,419
the people who were doing a good job.

1251
00:51:02,880 --> 00:51:04,009
Right. And so,

1252
00:51:04,640 --> 00:51:07,295
well, if you have to start where you are

1253
00:51:07,320 --> 00:51:09,815
and you're grateful for the opportunity and you

1254
00:51:09,840 --> 00:51:12,518
make the proper sacrifices and you work,

1255
00:51:12,800 --> 00:51:16,560
then anyone with any sense will notice that.

1256
00:51:16,880 --> 00:51:19,800
And anyone you want to work for has enough

1257
00:51:19,960 --> 00:51:22,400
sense to notice when you're doing a good job.

1258
00:51:22,569 --> 00:51:25,415
Now, if you're in a job where you're doing a good

1259
00:51:25,440 --> 00:51:26,772
job and no one is noticing,

1260
00:51:26,814 --> 00:51:28,720
you should ask yourself two questions.

1261
00:51:29,600 --> 00:51:31,415
Do the people that you're working

1262
00:51:31,440 --> 00:51:34,015
for know that you're doing a good job?

1263
00:51:34,040 --> 00:51:36,615
Because it's possible that you're doing things so

1264
00:51:36,640 --> 00:51:38,800
efficiently that you're invisible and you're not

1265
00:51:38,825 --> 00:51:40,455
very good at self-promotion,

1266
00:51:40,480 --> 00:51:42,535
which is actually just communication.

1267
00:51:42,661 --> 00:51:44,600
If you're doing a good job for people,

1268
00:51:44,920 --> 00:51:46,497
they need to know it.

1269
00:51:46,640 --> 00:51:48,707
And one of the times that you can

1270
00:51:49,280 --> 00:51:51,735
inform them about that is when you

1271
00:51:51,760 --> 00:51:53,440
go ask for a raise or a promotion.

1272
00:51:53,753 --> 00:51:54,895
You need a little list.

1273
00:51:54,920 --> 00:51:57,048
"Here's a bunch of things I did that made your

1274
00:51:57,089 --> 00:51:59,455
life a hell of a lot easier than it might have

1275
00:51:59,480 --> 00:52:01,800
otherwise been, and perhaps more profitable,"

1276
00:52:02,192 --> 00:52:04,560
that you may not have even known about.

1277
00:52:05,195 --> 00:52:07,975
"And if you produce an increment of salary of this

1278
00:52:08,000 --> 00:52:10,855
magnitude or give me a bit more flexibility or

1279
00:52:10,880 --> 00:52:12,760
a promotion or some other opportunity,

1280
00:52:12,785 --> 00:52:14,729
here's a bunch of things I could do for you

1281
00:52:14,771 --> 00:52:16,814
that would make your life even better."

1282
00:52:16,840 --> 00:52:20,120
It's like, if you have that story and it's real,

1283
00:52:20,360 --> 00:52:22,255
and you present that to your employer,

1284
00:52:22,280 --> 00:52:23,255
and they don't go,

1285
00:52:23,840 --> 00:52:26,080
"That sounds like a pretty damn good deal.

1286
00:52:26,113 --> 00:52:28,255
Are you sure that that raise is enough?",

1287
00:52:28,280 --> 00:52:31,305
then maybe you should decide whether or not

1288
00:52:31,520 --> 00:52:33,953
that's not the right place for you to be working.

1289
00:52:34,037 --> 00:52:36,080
And before you do that, too,

1290
00:52:36,160 --> 00:52:38,455
you might have already wanted to get your CV

1291
00:52:38,480 --> 00:52:41,895
in order and to have started sending it out to see

1292
00:52:41,920 --> 00:52:43,962
what sort of market demand there is for your

1293
00:52:44,003 --> 00:52:46,360
skills, so you can tell your employer as well

1294
00:52:46,640 --> 00:52:49,091
that you have other offers that are pending.

1295
00:52:49,299 --> 00:52:51,040
And then you put yourself in a pretty

1296
00:52:51,065 --> 00:52:52,615
damn good bargaining position.

1297
00:52:52,640 --> 00:52:53,970
Part of the reason, by the way,

1298
00:52:54,012 --> 00:52:56,222
that women do not make as much money as men—

1299
00:52:56,264 --> 00:52:57,306
it's one of many reasons—

1300
00:52:57,348 --> 00:52:59,475
is that they're not as good as men

1301
00:52:59,516 --> 00:53:01,268
at promoting their own accomplishments.

1302
00:53:01,643 --> 00:53:03,175
It's part of being agreeable

1303
00:53:03,200 --> 00:53:04,896
and higher in negative emotion.

1304
00:53:04,937 --> 00:53:08,935
I saw this when I worked in civil service in

1305
00:53:08,960 --> 00:53:11,735
Alberta, years ago, when I was a kid, 20 years old.

1306
00:53:11,880 --> 00:53:14,960
I saw that the bureaucracy was basically run

1307
00:53:15,360 --> 00:53:19,040
by 50-year-old women who did all the work,

1308
00:53:21,118 --> 00:53:25,329
and all of that credit was taken by narcissists

1309
00:53:25,371 --> 00:53:28,457
who pretended that it was them and took all

1310
00:53:28,499 --> 00:53:30,083
the credit from the conscientious

1311
00:53:30,125 --> 00:53:31,710
older women who were working.

1312
00:53:31,760 --> 00:53:33,400
Right, an ugly situation.

1313
00:53:33,670 --> 00:53:35,338
And you could lay that at the feet

1314
00:53:35,379 --> 00:53:36,760
of the narcissists for being

1315
00:53:36,960 --> 00:53:39,520
manipulative and psychopathic.

1316
00:53:39,600 --> 00:53:42,935
But those women should have learned that doing

1317
00:53:42,960 --> 00:53:45,720
a great job invisibly is not a very good strategy.

1318
00:53:46,055 --> 00:53:47,181
People need to know.

1319
00:53:47,223 --> 00:53:49,349
And that means you shouldn't be tooting your own

1320
00:53:49,391 --> 00:53:51,643
horn constantly because that's just annoying.

1321
00:53:51,685 --> 00:53:54,335
But it does mean that the people for whom you're

1322
00:53:54,360 --> 00:53:56,765
doing a good job should know you're doing it.

1323
00:53:57,266 --> 00:54:00,655
And you should also note how much

1324
00:54:00,680 --> 00:54:02,895
reward you need for doing a good job.

1325
00:54:02,920 --> 00:54:05,029
Because if you're doing a great job and no one

1326
00:54:05,071 --> 00:54:07,651
ever notices, maybe you're conscientious enough so

1327
00:54:07,676 --> 00:54:10,200
that that'll be sufficiently motivating for you.

1328
00:54:10,240 --> 00:54:12,948
But most of us would like to be rewarded

1329
00:54:12,973 --> 00:54:16,280
for a job well done on some schedule.

1330
00:54:16,305 --> 00:54:18,249
That's something else you can negotiate

1331
00:54:18,287 --> 00:54:20,560
with your wife, your husband, your kids.

1332
00:54:21,280 --> 00:54:22,060
It's like,

1333
00:54:24,280 --> 00:54:26,714
one of you in a marriage is going to cook.

1334
00:54:27,200 --> 00:54:29,842
Well, a little appreciation for that now and then

1335
00:54:30,120 --> 00:54:32,960
tends to improve the quality of the meals,

1336
00:54:33,600 --> 00:54:36,495
and the atmosphere around the table.

1337
00:54:36,520 --> 00:54:37,973
One of the things you have to

1338
00:54:38,015 --> 00:54:39,475
discover about yourself,

1339
00:54:39,800 --> 00:54:42,352
and this is also part of developing a vision is,

1340
00:54:43,160 --> 00:54:46,040
well, what's the reward schedule

1341
00:54:46,065 --> 00:54:47,565
that's necessary for you?

1342
00:54:47,960 --> 00:54:51,480
And none, that's not a good reward schedule.

1343
00:54:51,560 --> 00:54:53,695
And it's something to discover, right?

1344
00:54:53,720 --> 00:54:56,408
Maybe someone only has to say something

1345
00:54:56,440 --> 00:54:58,080
positive to you once every month.

1346
00:54:58,640 --> 00:54:59,215
Who knows?

1347
00:54:59,240 --> 00:55:00,784
Or maybe it's twice a day.

1348
00:55:01,200 --> 00:55:03,160
There's going to be some temperamental

1349
00:55:03,480 --> 00:55:06,080
variability that characterizes you in that regard.

1350
00:55:06,122 --> 00:55:08,207
You're probably going to need to be rewarded

1351
00:55:08,249 --> 00:55:11,400
more for things that you're just trying as well.

1352
00:55:12,240 --> 00:55:15,520
But this is a good thing to meditate on.

1353
00:55:15,840 --> 00:55:17,455
How much notice do you need when

1354
00:55:17,480 --> 00:55:18,799
you're doing something good?

1355
00:55:18,841 --> 00:55:19,967
And this is something

1356
00:55:20,008 --> 00:55:21,725
to negotiate with your partner.

1357
00:55:21,760 --> 00:55:23,845
When you do something for them,

1358
00:55:25,360 --> 00:55:29,415
you can teach them to notice it, and you can

1359
00:55:29,440 --> 00:55:31,435
also let them know what they need to say.

1360
00:55:31,476 --> 00:55:34,280
This is something else that's useful to know.

1361
00:55:36,040 --> 00:55:38,274
Say you're having a dispute with your wife,

1362
00:55:38,399 --> 00:55:41,026
and she wanted you to say

1363
00:55:41,068 --> 00:55:43,160
something other than what you said.

1364
00:55:43,194 --> 00:55:44,529
Now, that's what she's going

1365
00:55:44,570 --> 00:55:46,155
to let you know, first of all.

1366
00:55:46,200 --> 00:55:47,855
"I would like you to say something

1367
00:55:47,880 --> 00:55:49,283
other than what you just said."

1368
00:55:49,324 --> 00:55:50,975
"What do you want me to say?"

1369
00:55:51,000 --> 00:55:52,920
Well, then she's going to say,

1370
00:55:53,160 --> 00:55:55,455
"Well, if you loved me, you'd know."

1371
00:55:55,480 --> 00:55:59,735
Everyone laughs when I make that joke.

1372
00:55:59,760 --> 00:56:02,120
Yeah, well, it's too vague.

1373
00:56:02,720 --> 00:56:04,600
It's like, "No, I want to know exactly

1374
00:56:05,080 --> 00:56:06,575
what you would want me to say.

1375
00:56:06,600 --> 00:56:08,507
If I could say to you what would make

1376
00:56:08,549 --> 00:56:10,207
you happiest, what would that be?"

1377
00:56:10,232 --> 00:56:11,551
Now you're in trouble because

1378
00:56:11,593 --> 00:56:13,094
you have to figure that out.

1379
00:56:13,120 --> 00:56:14,640
Then you have to reveal that.

1380
00:56:14,679 --> 00:56:16,597
Then you're going to be annoyed because you're

1381
00:56:16,639 --> 00:56:18,307
going to say, "Well, that's not genuine."

1382
00:56:18,349 --> 00:56:19,641
It's like, yeah,

1383
00:56:19,960 --> 00:56:22,269
maybe it won't be the first 20 times.

1384
00:56:23,560 --> 00:56:26,775
But maybe the person can get good at it,

1385
00:56:26,800 --> 00:56:29,000
and by the 50th compliment,

1386
00:56:29,800 --> 00:56:31,695
not only will have the words right,

1387
00:56:31,720 --> 00:56:33,570
but they'll also have the sentiment right.

1388
00:56:33,611 --> 00:56:35,775
You have to let people be stupid about how

1389
00:56:35,800 --> 00:56:38,440
they're treating you well to begin with.

1390
00:56:38,600 --> 00:56:40,960
The other thing you can notice, too,

1391
00:56:41,118 --> 00:56:43,720
is that if your partner does do something

1392
00:56:44,200 --> 00:56:46,280
that you really appreciated,

1393
00:56:47,081 --> 00:56:49,295
something small and subtle, let's say,

1394
00:56:49,320 --> 00:56:51,895
they sneak something good in just to see what

1395
00:56:51,920 --> 00:56:54,255
might happen, if you're smart enough to jump

1396
00:56:54,280 --> 00:56:56,695
on that, and you have to not be too resentful

1397
00:56:56,720 --> 00:56:58,480
about their existence to do this,

1398
00:56:58,590 --> 00:57:00,800
if you're smart enough to jump on that and say,

1399
00:57:00,825 --> 00:57:02,469
"Ha, I saw what you did.

1400
00:57:02,760 --> 00:57:05,055
This is how you greeted me when I came home.

1401
00:57:05,080 --> 00:57:07,320
I got a hug, for example, instead of an immediate

1402
00:57:07,345 --> 00:57:09,516
litany of never-ending complaints.

1403
00:57:09,560 --> 00:57:12,855
That was a very lovely way to reenter the house."

1404
00:57:13,160 --> 00:57:15,440
If you're very, very—this is something that's

1405
00:57:15,480 --> 00:57:17,815
very useful with employees, too, and coworkers.

1406
00:57:17,840 --> 00:57:21,175
If you see someone doing a good job and you say,

1407
00:57:21,200 --> 00:57:23,028
"Hey, here's what you did,"

1408
00:57:23,069 --> 00:57:24,487
and you say it in detail,

1409
00:57:24,520 --> 00:57:27,040
"I saw that and it was good," man,

1410
00:57:27,480 --> 00:57:29,533
you do that a hundred times if you're

1411
00:57:29,658 --> 00:57:30,800
running a restaurant,

1412
00:57:30,880 --> 00:57:32,540
you do that to your employees,

1413
00:57:33,080 --> 00:57:35,040
any of the employees worth keeping,

1414
00:57:35,079 --> 00:57:37,081
they'll be working themselves to the bone

1415
00:57:37,123 --> 00:57:38,916
to get another reward like that.

1416
00:57:38,960 --> 00:57:40,320
People really like that.

1417
00:57:40,781 --> 00:57:44,040
The Skinner, the Skinner behavioral psychologist,

1418
00:57:44,504 --> 00:57:46,172
could train animals to do anything.

1419
00:57:46,214 --> 00:57:49,415
He trained pigeons to guide guided missiles

1420
00:57:49,440 --> 00:57:52,160
over enemy territory by pecking on photographs.

1421
00:57:52,920 --> 00:57:53,845
That's hard.

1422
00:57:55,160 --> 00:57:57,975
Skinner noticed that reward was the most effective

1423
00:57:58,000 --> 00:57:59,615
form of behavioral transformation,

1424
00:57:59,640 --> 00:58:02,852
but it was subtle, because to reward an animal

1425
00:58:03,186 --> 00:58:05,135
for doing something you want it to do,

1426
00:58:05,160 --> 00:58:07,935
you have to wait around until it does the thing,

1427
00:58:07,960 --> 00:58:10,227
and then you have to reward them.

1428
00:58:10,275 --> 00:58:12,068
And so this is the same in your household.

1429
00:58:12,110 --> 00:58:14,095
If you're watching your kids, maybe your kid

1430
00:58:14,120 --> 00:58:16,733
by accident cleaned something up one day.

1431
00:58:19,158 --> 00:58:20,815
You can notice that.

1432
00:58:20,840 --> 00:58:23,800
You say, look, maybe they're five.

1433
00:58:23,828 --> 00:58:25,163
"That was the sort of thing

1434
00:58:25,204 --> 00:58:26,735
an eight-year-old would do.

1435
00:58:26,760 --> 00:58:28,255
Good work, kid.

1436
00:58:28,280 --> 00:58:29,750
Here's what you did."

1437
00:58:29,791 --> 00:58:31,501
They'll smile like mad.

1438
00:58:31,720 --> 00:58:33,935
And the probability that they'll do something

1439
00:58:33,960 --> 00:58:36,420
like that again radically magnifies.

1440
00:58:36,503 --> 00:58:38,800
And kids are very good at generalizing, too.

1441
00:58:39,160 --> 00:58:42,015
So not only will they do that thing again,

1442
00:58:42,040 --> 00:58:44,600
but they'll do things in that category again.

1443
00:58:45,120 --> 00:58:47,775
And that's a fun way of interacting with people

1444
00:58:47,800 --> 00:58:51,175
in your family, because targeted reward

1445
00:58:51,200 --> 00:58:54,615
is a pleasure to give and also to receive.

1446
00:58:54,640 --> 00:58:57,415
And so it's a great way of establishing harmony

1447
00:58:57,440 --> 00:59:00,920
in your household without the scraps,

1448
00:59:00,945 --> 00:59:02,861
the fights that might otherwise be necessary.

1449
00:59:02,902 --> 00:59:04,615
Sometimes you have to settle something,

1450
00:59:04,640 --> 00:59:07,695
and that requires dredging up all sorts of things

1451
00:59:07,720 --> 00:59:10,735
that everyone perhaps would rather leave buried,

1452
00:59:10,760 --> 00:59:12,619
and attempting to sort through them.

1453
00:59:12,800 --> 00:59:13,975
That's quite demanding.

1454
00:59:14,000 --> 00:59:17,495
But targeted reward requires attention,

1455
00:59:17,520 --> 00:59:20,720
but it's extremely effective and it's

1456
00:59:20,960 --> 00:59:22,680
a very pleasant thing to engage in.

1457
00:59:22,961 --> 00:59:24,837
All right, so there may be things in your

1458
00:59:24,879 --> 00:59:27,006
present that you have to sort out.

1459
00:59:27,048 --> 00:59:28,335
Maybe you have to find your

1460
00:59:28,360 --> 00:59:29,840
damn CV on your computer.

1461
00:59:29,883 --> 00:59:31,320
Even that can be a nightmare.

1462
00:59:31,345 --> 00:59:34,186
One of the things I saw with my particularly

1463
00:59:34,269 --> 00:59:37,855
disorganized clients was that I'd ask them to get

1464
00:59:37,880 --> 00:59:39,183
their CV off their computer,

1465
00:59:39,224 --> 00:59:41,015
and then maybe they'd bring their laptop in,

1466
00:59:41,040 --> 00:59:42,102
and the whole bloody thing

1467
00:59:42,143 --> 00:59:43,535
was just a catastrophic mess.

1468
00:59:43,560 --> 00:59:44,880
There were files everywhere.

1469
00:59:44,905 --> 00:59:47,215
The computer hard drive was

1470
00:59:47,240 --> 00:59:49,316
a reflection of their psyche.

1471
00:59:49,880 --> 00:59:51,815
Everything was everywhere,

1472
00:59:51,840 --> 00:59:54,920
and all that was valuable was lost.

1473
00:59:55,040 --> 00:59:57,080
And so maybe one of the things that,

1474
00:59:57,280 --> 00:59:59,935
the first thing you have to encounter when you try

1475
00:59:59,960 --> 01:00:02,160
to open your CV is the fact that your computer is

1476
01:00:02,202 --> 01:00:04,758
such a bloody mess that you can't find anything.

1477
01:00:04,787 --> 01:00:07,920
Imagine that, just imagine that.

1478
01:00:08,160 --> 01:00:09,800
So someone's in a job they hate.

1479
01:00:10,240 --> 01:00:11,615
And in order to fix that,

1480
01:00:11,640 --> 01:00:14,671
they have to sort out their CV.

1481
01:00:14,712 --> 01:00:16,130
And to do that, they have to find it.

1482
01:00:16,172 --> 01:00:17,798
And to do that, they have to confront their

1483
01:00:17,840 --> 01:00:19,840
computer, which isn't that big a dragon.

1484
01:00:20,065 --> 01:00:22,818
It's not nothing, but it's not cancer.

1485
01:00:23,600 --> 01:00:24,495
It's trouble.

1486
01:00:24,520 --> 01:00:27,055
But then that's annoying and embarrassing.

1487
01:00:27,080 --> 01:00:29,475
And so instead of doing that, they don't do it.

1488
01:00:29,516 --> 01:00:32,018
And then they have the job they hate for 30 years.

1489
01:00:32,440 --> 01:00:35,104
Right. Yeah.

1490
01:00:35,146 --> 01:00:36,355
Not smart.

1491
01:00:36,920 --> 01:00:40,175
And you could also see that there's a certain

1492
01:00:40,200 --> 01:00:43,895
humility involved in noticing that your failure

1493
01:00:43,920 --> 01:00:45,321
to confront the mess on your

1494
01:00:45,363 --> 01:00:47,323
computer might end your life.

1495
01:00:48,600 --> 01:00:49,992
Right.